010\n*[http://jsjacobs.scripts.mit.edu/evenjoshknows/?p=119/ \"Amherst Poets Dream Date: Interview with Dan Chiasson\"] by Josh Jacobs, September 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chiasson, Dan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Poets from Vermont]]\n[[Category:Poets from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Amherst College faculty]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College faculty]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Sudbury, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:American male essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dan on Boat.JPG|thumb|Dan Chiasson]]\n'''Dan Chiasson''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t\u0283|e\u026a|s|\u0259n}}; born May 9, 1971<ref>[http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poet/dan-chiasson Dan Chiasson] at poets.org.</ref> in [[Burlington, Vermont]]) is an American poet, critic, and journalist. The Sewanee Review called Chiasson \"the country\u2019s most visible poet-critic.\" He is the Lorraine C. Wang Professor of English Literature at [[Wellesley College]].\n\nChiasson is the author of six books: The Afterlife of Objects (University of Chicago Press, 2002), Natural History (Alfred A. Knopf, 2005), One Kind of Everything: Poem and Person in Contemporary America (University of Chicago Press, 2007), Where's the Moon, There's the Moon (Alfred A. Knopf, 2010), Bicentennial (Alfred A. Knopf, 2014) and The Math Campers (Alfred A. Knopf, 2020).\n\n==Life==\nChiasson grew up in Burlington, Vermont, where he attended Mater Christi School and Rice Memorial High School, from which he graduated in 1989.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 5, 1989 |title=Rice memorial High School Graduates |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/198843788/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=3B |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He graduated summa cum laude in Classics and English from [[Amherst College]]<ref>[https://www.amherst.edu/aboutamherst/magazine/issues/2009summer/amherstcreates/chiasson \"Poet, Critic and Editor Dan Chiasson '93\"], Amherst College, 2009.</ref> (1993), and from [[Harvard University]], where he received a Ph.D in English and was awarded the Whiting Foundation Award in the Humanities.\n\nIn addition to teaching at Wellesley, Chiasson has been affiliated with Boston University's Master of Fine Arts program, with NYU's program in Paris, France, and with the Middlebury College Bread Load Environmental Conference in Ripton, Vt. He lives in [[Wellesley, Massachusetts]], with his wife and two sons.\n\nHe is the poetry critic for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', as well as a regular contributor to ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', where he writes about poetry, pop music and film.\nHe was the poetry editor (with Meghan O'Rourke) and later advisory editor, of the ''[[Paris Review]]''.<ref>[http://www.theparisreview.org/page.php/prmID/17 \"Msthead\"],\n ''The Paris Review''.</ref> His poems have been translated into many languages, including German by Jan Wagner. His \"Natural History\" was published as \"Naturgeschichte\" at Luxbooks, a publishing house focused on American poetry in bilingual editions. In the UK, he is published by [[Bloodaxe Books]].\n\nHe is on the editorial board of the literary magazine ''[[The Common (magazine)|The Common]]'', based at [[Amherst College]].<ref>[http://www.thecommononline.org/about \"About The Common\".]</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* 2008 Award in Literature, American Academy of Arts and Letters \n* 2008 [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] for poetry <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/2550-dan-chiasson |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211021747/http://gf.org/fellows/2550-Dan-Chiasson |archive-date=2009-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wellesley.edu/PublicAffairs/Releases/2008/040908.html \"Wellesley\u2019s Dan Chiasson Is Named a 2008 Guggenheim Fellow\"], Wellesley College, April 9, 2008.</ref>\n* 2004 [[Whiting Awards|Whiting Award]]\n\n==Bibliography==\nSee also links in the [[Dan Chiasson#External links|External links section]] below.\n{{Expand list|date=December 2014}}\n\n===Poetry===\n;Collections\n* {{cite book |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=  |title=The afterlife of objects |location=Chicago |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=2002 |<!--isbn=978-0-226-10378-5-->}}\n* {{cite book |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |title=Natural history : poems |location=New York |publisher=Random House |year=2007 |<!--isbn=978-0-375-71115-2-->}}\n* {{cite book |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |title=Where's the moon, there's the moon : poems |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |year=2010 |<!--isbn=978-0-307-27217-1-->}}\n* {{cite book |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |title=Bicentennial : poems |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |year=2014 |<!--isbn=9780385349819-->}}\n;Anthologies\n* {{cite book |title=New voices : contemporary poetry from the United States |editor=Hix, H. L. |editorlink=H. L. Hix |publisher= Irish Pages |year=2008|<!--isbn=978-0-9544257-9-1-->}}\n;List of poems\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n|-\n|From 'The Names of 1,001 Strangers'\n|2017\n|{{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask= |date=May 1, 2017 |title=From 'The Names of 1,001 Strangers' |department= |journal=The New Yorker |volume=93 |issue=11 |pages=38\u201339 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/05/01/from-the-names-of-1001-strangers |<!--accessdate=2017-08-25-->}}\n|\n|-\n|Obituary\n|2014\n|{{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |date=January 6, 2014 |title=Obituary |department= |journal=The Ne