y, Illusion\" |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=89 |issue=34 |pages=78\u201379 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/10/28/the-ghost-writer-3 |<!--accessdate=2017-06-18-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=February 10, 2014 |title=Bet the farm : Robert Frrost's turbulent apprenticeship |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=89 |issue=48 |pages=72\u201376 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/02/10/bet-the-farm |<!--accessdate=2018-04-10-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=June 2, 2014 |title=Mother tongue : poetry and prose by Rachel Zucker |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=90 |issue=15 |pages=77\u201379 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/06/02/mother-tongue-4 |<!--accessdate=2015-04-22-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=October 20, 2014 |title=View from the mountain : new poems by Louise Gl\u00fcck |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=90 |issue=32 |pages=95\u201397 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/10/20/view-mountain |<!--accessdate=2014-12-23-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=April 13, 2015 |title=Out of this world : James Merrill's supernatural muse |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=91 |issue=8 |pages=70\u201374 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/13/out-of-this-world-books-dan-chiasson |<!--accessdate=2015-06-22-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=March 21, 2016 |title=The tenderness trap : Robyn Schiff and the poetry of ordinary terror |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=92 |issue=6 |pages=89\u201390 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/03/21/a-woman-of-property-by-robyn-schiff |<!--accessdate=2016-10-25-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=June 20, 2016 |title=Boundary conditions : Adrienne Rich's collected poems |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=92 |issue=18 |pages=78\u201381 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/06/20/adrienne-richs-art-and-activism |<!--accessdate=2017-05-26-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=August 8\u201315, 2016 |title=Childhood's end : a debut about life, language, and what binds them |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=92 |issue=24 |pages=75\u201377 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/08/08/the-after-party-by-jana-prikryl |<!--accessdate=2017-12-20-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"Poetry of a childhood lost\".</ref> Reviews {{cite book |author=Prikryl, Jana |authormask= |title=The after party |location= |publisher=Tim Duggan Books |year= |<!--isbn=-->}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=December 4, 2017 |title=One man's trash : how A. R. Ammons turned the everyday into art |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=93 |issue=39 |pages=69\u201372 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/12/04/the-great-american-poet-of-daily-chores |<!--accessdate=2018-03-26-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"The great American poet of daily chores\".</ref>\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=February 11, 2019 |title=Song of my selves : Shane McRae's poems to America |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=94 |issue=48 |pages=68\u201369 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/02/11/shane-mccraes-poems-to-america |<!--accessdate=2019-08-02-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"Shane McRae's poems to America\".</ref>\n* {{cite journal |author=Chiasson, Dan |authormask=1 |date=June 3, 2019 |title=Bittersweet : Natalie Scenters-Zapico's poems evoke damage and repair |department=The Critics. Books |journal=The New Yorker |volume=95 |issue=15 |pages=65\u201367 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/06/03/the-bittersweet-poetry-of-lima-limon |<!--accessdate=2019-08-17-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"The bittersweet poetry of 'Lima :: Lim\u00f3n'\".</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.newyorker.com/search?qt=dismax&sort=score+desc&query=chiasson&submit=/ Search for Chiasson's work] in ''The New Yorker''\n*[http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/dan-chiasson-2/ Search for Chiasson's work] in ''The New York Review of Books''\n*[http://www.theparisreview.org/search?q=dan+chiasson&x=0&y=0/ Search for Chiasson's work] in ''The Paris Review''\n*[http://www.whiting.org/awards/winners/dan-chiasson#/ Profile] at The Whiting Foundation\n*[http://www.radioopensource.org/whose-words-these-are-27-dan-chiasson-the-natural/ Dan Chiasson interviewed by Christopher Lydon], \"Whose Words These Are,\" Radio Open Source, May 27, 2010\n*[http://jsjacobs.scripts.mit.edu/evenjoshknows/?p=119/ \"Amherst Poets Dream Date: Interview with Dan Chiasson\"] by Josh Jacobs, September 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chiasson, Dan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Poets from Vermont]]\n[[Category:Poets from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Amherst College faculty]]\n[[Category:Wellesley College faculty]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Sudbury, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:American male essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n", "name_user": "Benjdavis83", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:misspelling, Bread Load -> Bread Loaf", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Chiasson"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Madagascar", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Madagascar}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Madagascar\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Madagascar]]\n| first_case      = [[Antananarivo]]\n| arrival_date    = 20 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 70\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Madagascar]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Measures==\n\nLockdowns were implemented in at least two cities.<ref name=\"Sumitomo halts\">{{cite news |title=Sumitomo halts mines in Bolivia, Madagascar |url=https://www.mining.com/sumitomo-halts-mines-in-bolivia-madagascar/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=MINING.COM |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The government announced on 17 March that all international and regional flights would be suspended for 30 days starting 20 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mg2.mofcom.gov.cn/article/chinanews/202003/20200302946118.shtml|title=Madagascar suspend toutes les liaisons a\u00e9riennes r\u00e9gionales et internationales|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=mofcom.gov.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nDue to the crisis, a lack of international tourists caused problems for the tourism industry.<ref name=\"Tourists departure\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-madagascar-tourism/tourists-departure-leaves-madagascar-forlorn-as-coronavirus-fears-bite-idUSKBN2171QM|title=Tourists' departure leaves Madagascar forlorn as coronavirus fears bite|date=20 March 2020|work=Reuters|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> [[Ambatovy mine]] suspended operations.<ref name=\"Sumitomo halts\"/> The [[Central Bank of Madagascar]] injected hundreds of billions of ariary into the banking system to ease the economic damage caused by [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madagascar's central bank injects cash to support economy due to virus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-madagascar-economy/madagascars-central-bank-injects-cash-to-support-economy-due-to-virus-idUSL8N2BH6J1 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 20 March, the first three cases were confirmed in Madagascar. All were women.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://actu.orange.mg/officiel-trois-premiers-cas-de-coronavirus-a-madagascar/ |title=Officiel trois premiers cas de Coronavirus \u00e0 Madagascar |work=Orange Madagascar |date=20 March 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Madagascar|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Madagascar]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Madagascar]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{Madagascar-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Madagascar}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Madagascar\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Madagascar]]\n| first_case      = [[Antananarivo]]\n| arrival_date    = 20 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 0\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 70\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Madagascar]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Measures==\n\nLockdowns were implemented in at least two cities.<ref name=\"Sumitomo halts\">{{cite news |title=Sumitomo halts mines in Bolivia, Madagascar |url=https://www.mining.com/sumitomo-halts-mines-in-bolivia-madagascar/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=MINING.COM |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The government announced on 17 March that all international and regional flights would be suspended for 30 days starting 20 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mg2.mofcom.gov.cn/article/chinanews/202003/20200302946118.shtml|title=Madagascar suspend toutes les liaisons a\u00e9riennes r\u00e9gionales et internationales|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=mofcom.gov.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nDue to the crisis, a lack of international tourists caused problems for the tourism industry.<ref name=\"Tourists departure\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-madagascar-tourism/tourists-departure-leaves-madagascar-forlorn-as-coronavirus-fears-bite-idUSKBN2171QM|title=Tourists' departure leaves Madagascar forlorn as coronavirus fears bite|date=20 March 2020|work=Reuters|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=en}}</ref> [[Ambatovy mine]] suspended operations.<ref name=\"Sumitomo halts\"/> The [[Central Bank of Madagascar]] injected hundreds of billions of ariary into the banking system to ease the economic damage caused by [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madagascar's central bank injects cash to support economy due to virus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-madagascar-economy/madagascars-central-bank-injects-cash-to-support-economy-due-to-virus-idUSL8N2BH6J1 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 20 March, the first three cases were confirmed in Madagascar. All were women.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://actu.orange.mg/officiel-trois-premiers-cas-de-coronavirus-a-madagascar/ |title=Officiel trois premiers cas de Coronavirus \u00e0 Madagascar |work=Orange Madagascar |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Madagascar|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Madagascar]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Madagascar]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{Madagascar-stub}}\n", "name_user": "NathanWoods", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added source language.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Madagascar"}
{"title_page": "Bad (album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Bad\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Michael Jackson]]\n| cover        = Michael Jackson - Bad.png\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = A man in his late twenties stands and looks forward. His hair is curly and black. He is wearing a black jacket that has several buckles and pants. The background is white and beside him are the words \"Michael Jackson\" in black capital letter, and over them, \"Bad\" in red.\n| released     = August 31, 1987\n| recorded     = January 1985 \u2013 July 1987{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}}\n| studio       = [[Westlake Recording Studios|Westlake]], [[Los Angeles]], California<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Quincy |last= Troupe |title= Michael Jackson's 1987 Cover Story: 'The Pressure to Beat It' |magazine= [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date= June 25, 2014 |accessdate= December 14, 2019\n|url= https://www.spin.com/2014/06/michael-jackson-bad-1987-cover-story/}}</ref>\n| genre        = <!--Sourced in the body of the article. Do not add unsourced genres -->{{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[rock music|rock]]|[[funk]]|[[rhythm and blues]]|[[dance music|dance]]|[[soul music|soul]]|[[hard rock]]}}\n| length       = \n| label        = {{hlist|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|[[Sony Music|CBS]]}}\n| producer     = [[Quincy Jones]]\n| prev_title   = [[Anthology (Michael Jackson album)|Anthology]]\n| prev_year    = 1986\n| next_title   = [[The Original Soul of Michael Jackson]]\n| next_year    = 1987\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Michael Jackson]] studio album\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]\n | prev_year  = 1982\n | title      = Bad\n | year       = 1987\n | next_title = [[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]\n | next_year  = 1991\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Bad\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[I Just Can't Stop Loving You]]\n | single1date = July 20, 1987\n | single2     = [[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\n | single2date = September 7, 1987\n | single3     = [[The Way You Make Me Feel]]\n | single3date = November 9, 1987\n | single4     = [[Man in the Mirror]]\n | single4date = February 6, 1988<ref>{{cite web|first= Steve |last= Sullivan |year= 2017 |title= Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings |volume= 3 & 4 |publisher= [[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn= 978-1-4422-5449-7 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=GQglDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA545}}</ref>\n | single5     = [[Dirty Diana]]\n | single5date = April 18, 1988\n | single6     = [[Another Part of Me]]\n | single6date = July 11, 1988\n | single7     = [[Smooth Criminal]]\n | single7date = November 14, 1988\n | single8     = [[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\n | single8date = February 13, 1989\n | single9     = [[Liberian Girl]]\n | single9date = July 4, 1989\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Bad''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American singer [[Michael Jackson]]. It was released on August 31, 1987 by [[Epic Records]], nearly five years after Jackson's previous album, ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]''. ''Bad'' was written and recorded in nearly a year, and was the final collaboration between Jackson and producer [[Quincy Jones]]. Jackson co-produced it and composed all but two tracks. The album features appearances from [[Siedah Garrett]] and [[Stevie Wonder]]. Incorporating [[pop music|pop]], [[dance music|dance]], [[funk]], [[soul music|soul]], [[Rock music|rock]] and [[hard rock]], Jackson experimented with new sounds, including [[digital synthesizer]] technology. The lyrical themes include [[media bias]], [[paranoia]], [[racial profiling]], [[Romance (love)|romance]], [[Self-help|self-improvement]] and [[world peace]].\n\nDescribed as \"the most anticipated album in history\", ''Bad'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and also reached number one in a then record-breaking 24 other countries. It sold over 2 million copies in its first week in the US, and 500,000 in its first five days in the UK. Nine songs were released as official singles, and one as a promotional single. Seven charted in the top 20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], including a [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones#Most number-one singles from one album|record-breaking five number ones]]: \"[[I Just Can't Stop Loving You]]\", \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\", \"[[The Way You Make Me Feel]]\", \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" and \"[[Dirty Diana]]\". The album remained in the top five on the ''Billboard'' 200 for 38 weeks, setting a record for the longest run in the top five by an album from a male solo artist. By 1989, it had become the second-best-selling album of all time at the time, behind ''Thriller'', having sold 22 million copies worldwide. It was also the best-selling album worldwide of 1988 and 1989.\n\n''Bad'' was promoted with the film, ''[[Moonwalker]]'' (1988), which included the music videos of songs from the album, including \"[[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]]\", \"[[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\", \"Man in the Mirror\" and \"[[Smooth Criminal]]\". The film became the best-selling [[home video]] of all time. At the [[30th Annual Grammy Awards|30th Grammy Awards]], Jackson performed \"The Way You Make Me Feel\" and \"Man in the Mirror\". The [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] tour, which was Jackson's first solo world tour, grossed $125 million (equivalent to $254 million in 2019) making it the [[List of highest-grossing concert tours#1980s|highest-grossing solo concert tour of the 1980s]]. Jackson performed 132 concerts in 15 countries to an audience of 4.4 million including a record seven sold-out shows at [[Wembley Stadium]]. The third concert on July 16, 1988, was attended by [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and [[Prince Charles]]. It was also his last tour where he performed in the United States. Jackson was entered into the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' three times from the tour.\n\n''Bad'' is one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]], with over 35 million copies sold worldwide. In February 2017, it was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). The album has been credited for redefining the sound of pop music and named by several publications as one of the greatest albums of all time. It was nominated for six [[Grammy Award]]s, winning [[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Recording \u2013 Non Classical]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]] (for \"Leave Me Alone\"). At the 1989 [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], Jackson received the first [[Billboard Music Award for Spotlight|Spotlight Award]] in recognition for being the first artist to have five number one singles from one album on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and ''Bad'' was awarded [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Album of the Year]]. Following the appraisal of the music videos for the singles from the album'','' along with his previous music videos throughout the 1980s, Jackson was awarded the [[Michael Jackson Video Vanguard Award|MTV Video Vanguard Artist of the Decade Award]].\n\n==Background==\nJackson's sixth solo album, ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'', was released in 1982 and by 1984 was certified [[music recording certification|20x Platinum]] by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|title= Gold & Platinum: Michael Jackson \u2013 Thriller |publisher= Recording Industry Association of America |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=michael+jackson&ti=thriller&format=Album&adv=SEARCH#search_section}}</ref> Due to the huge commercial success of ''Thriller'' and the expectations of its follow up, Jackson aimed to sell 100 million copies with his next album.<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite magazine|first= John |last= Murph |title= Michael Jackson's 'Bad' Just Wasn't That Good |magazine= [[The Atlantic]] |date= September 19, 2012 |accessdate= January 15, 2020 |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/09/michael-jacksons-bad-just-wasnt-that-good/262551/}}</ref>\n\nThe four years following ''Thriller'' were marred by Jackson's rifts with [[Jackson family|his family]] and the [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], broken friendships with celebrities, and the pressure of celebrity. Reports spread of his [[Health and appearance of Michael Jackson|changing physical appearance]] and eccentric behavior. In 1987, ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' wrote that \"in record time, [Jackson] has gone from being one of the most admired of celebrities to one of the most absurd. And the pressure to restore himself in the public eye is paralyzing him.\"<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite magazine|first= Quincy |last= Troupe |title= Michael Jackson's 1987 Cover Story: 'The Pressure to Beat It' |magazine= [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date= June 25, 2014 |accessdate= February 15, 2019 |url= https://www.spin.com/2014/06/michael-jackson-bad-1987-cover-story/}}</ref> According to some associates, Jackson was nervous about completing his next album: \"He's reminded that everyone is waiting for this record and he goes into a shell. He is frightened.\"<ref name=\"Spin\"/>\n\nAfter Jackson had written a handful of the tracks on ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller'', producer [[Quincy Jones]] encouraged him to write more for ''Bad.'' Jones recalled: \"All the turmoil [in Jackson's life] was starting to mount up, so I said I thought it was time for him to do a very honest album.\"<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|first= Elias |last= Leight |title= Quincy Jones Looks Back on the Making of Michael Jackson's 'Bad' |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |date= August 30, 2017 |accessdate= February 15, 2019 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/quincy-jones-looks-back-on-the-making-of-michael-jacksons-bad-117216/}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n''Bad'' was Jackson's final collaboration with co-producer [[Quincy Jones]], who had produced ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller''.<ref name=\"linernotes\">{{cite AV media notes|title= Bad: Special Edition |year= 2001 |type= booklet |publisher= [[Epic Records]]}}</ref> Jackson began recording demos for the anticipated follow-up to ''Thriller'' in November 1983 while recording ''[[Victory (The Jacksons album)|Victory]]'' with [[the Jacksons]].{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}} Work was disrupted in July 1984, when Jackson embarked on the [[Victory Tour (The Jacksons tour)|Victory Tour]] with his brothers.{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}} Work resumed after the tour ended and after recording [[We Are the World]], and recording officially began in January 1985.{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}} In early 1985, work was disrupted again so Jackson could prepare for [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]'s 4D film experience [[Captain EO]], which featured an early pre-album extended cut of \"Another Part of Me.\"{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}} Work in the studio resumed in August of that year and continued until November 1986, when Jackson filmed the \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\" music video.{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}} Recording resumed in January 1987 and the album was completed in July.{{sfn|Smallcombe|2016|pp=220\u2013296}}\n\nJackson spent much of 1985 to 1987 out of the public eye, writing and recording at his home studio in [[Encino, Los Angeles]], with a group of musicians and engineers including [[Bill Bottrell]] known as the \"B team\".<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> The demos were brought to Westlake Studio to be finished by the \"A team\", with Jones and engineer [[Bruce Swedien]].<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Jones said the team would stay up for days on end when they \"were on a roll\": \"They were carrying second engineers out on stretchers. I was smoking 180 cigarettes a day.\"<ref name=\"RS\"/>\n\nJackson was eager to find innovative sounds and was interested in new musical technology.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> The team made extensive use of new [[digital synthesizer]]s, including [[Frequency modulation synthesis|FM synthesis]] and the [[Fairlight CMI]] and [[Synclavier PSMT]] synthesizers. They sometimes combined synthesizers to create new sounds.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Jackson hired Synclavier expert and sound designer Denny Jaeger to create sounds used on \"Dirty Diana\" and \"Smooth Criminal\".<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/>\n\nJackson wrote a reported 60 songs, and recorded 30, wanting to use them all on a 3-disc set.<ref name=\"otherinfo\">{{cite web|title= Michael Jackson's Life & Legacy: The Eccentric King of Pop (1986\u20131999) |url= http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1615214/20090702/jackson_michael.jhtml |publisher= [[VH1]] |date= June 7, 2009 |archivedate= June 4, 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110604141950/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1615214/20090702/jackson_michael.jhtml}}</ref> Jones suggested that the album be cut down to a ten-track single LP.<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/> When the album was released on CD, an 11th track, \"[[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\", was included.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> It was later released as a single. Later reissues of the LP also include this song. Jackson is credited for writing all but three songs on the album.<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/> Other writing credits included Terry Britten and Graham Lyle for \"Just Good Friends\" and [[Siedah Garrett]] and [[Glen Ballard]] for \"Man in the Mirror\".<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n{{Listen|filename=Michael Jackson - Bad.ogg|title=Bad (1987) |description=A 25-second sample of the chorus from \"Bad\". Some critics interpreted the song as a boast of Jackson's fame.}}\n''Bad'' is musically a heavier and more \"aggressive\" record than ''Thriller'', with Jackson moving away from the heavy-[[Groove (music)|groove]] sound and high-pitched vocals which featured on both ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller''.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> ''Bad'' primarily incorporates [[pop music|pop]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[funk]] and [[rhythm and blues|R&B]],<ref>{{cite news|first= Catherine |last= Gee |title= Michael Jackson: how Thriller and Bad changed music |date= November 30, 2012 |accessdate= January 15, 2020 |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/michael-jackson/9714186/Michael-Jackson-Time-to-remember-such-a-talented-musician.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Bernadette |last= McNulty |title= Michael Jackson's music: the solo albums |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= June 26, 2009 |accessdate= February 29, 2020 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/michael-jackson/5652389/Michael-Jacksons-music-the-solo-albums.html}}</ref> but also explores other genres such as [[soul music|soul]]<ref name=\"Latimes\">{{cite news|first= Richard |last= Cromelin |title= Michael Jackson has a good thing in 'Bad' |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date= August 31, 1987 |accessdate= October 15, 2019 |url= http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-archive-bad-review-aug31,0,7286392.story}}</ref> and [[hard rock]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] noted that ''Bad'' moved Jackson \"deeper into hard rock, deeper into schmaltzy [[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]], deeper into hard dance \u2013 essentially taking each portion of ''Thriller'' to an extreme, while increasing the quotient of immaculate studiocraft.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n\n{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Michael Jackson - Dirty Diana.ogg|title=Dirty Diana|description=The lyrics to \"Dirty Diana\" pertain to a groupie.<ref name=\"Latimes\"/>|format=[[Ogg]]}} The album's song lyrics relate to romance and paranoia, the latter being a recurring theme in Jackson's albums.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|first= Stephen Thomas |last= Erlewine |authorlink= Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Bad |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= February 15, 2011 |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/bad-mw0000650293}}</ref> \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\" was originally intended as a duet between Jackson and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/> Jackson also planned duets with [[Diana Ross]], [[Whitney Houston]], [[Aretha Franklin]] and [[Barbra Streisand]].<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/> The song was viewed as a revived \"[[Hit the Road Jack]]\" progression with lyrics that pertain to boasting.<ref name=\"Sigerson\">{{cite magazine|last=Sigerson|first=Davitt|date=October 22, 1987|title=Michael Jackson \u2013 Bad|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/bad-19871022|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> \"Dirty Diana\" was viewed by AllMusic's Stephen Thomas Erlewine as [[Misogyny|misogynistic]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> and its lyrics, describing a sexual predator, do not aim for the \"darkness\" of \"Billie Jean\", instead sounding equally intrigued by and apprehensive of a sexual challenge, while having the opportunity to accept or resist it.<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> \"Leave Me Alone\" was described as being a \"paranoid anthem\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> \"Man in the Mirror\" was seen as Jackson going \"a step further\" and offering \"a straightforward [[homily]] of personal commitment\", which can be seen in the lyrics, \"I'm starting with the man in the mirror / I'm asking him to change his ways / And no message could have been any clearer / If you wanna make the world a better place / Take a look at yourself and then make a change.\"<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/>\n\n{{Listen|filename=Michael Jackson - The Way You Make Me Feel (Album Version).ogg|title=\"The Way You Make Me Feel (1987)\" |description=\"The Way You Make Me Feel\", a love song.}}\n\n\"Liberian Girl\"'s lyrics were viewed as \"glistening\" with \"gratitude\" for the \"existence of a loved one\".<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> \"Smooth Criminal\"'s recalled \"the popcorn-chomping manner\" of \"Thriller\".<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> The track was thought of as an example of \"Jackson's free-form language\" that keeps people \"aware that we are on the edge of several realities: the film, the dream it inspires, the waking world it illuminates\".<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> The music in \"I Just Can't Stop Loving You\", a duet with Siedah Garrett, consisted mainly of finger snaps and timpani.<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> \"Just Good Friends\", a duet with [[Stevie Wonder]], was viewed by critics as sounding good at the beginning of the song, ending with a \"chin-bobbing cheerfulness\".<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> However, Jones said later: \"I made a mistake with ['Just Good Friends']. That didn't work.\"<ref name=\"RS\"/>\n\n\"The Way You Make Me Feel\" consists of blues harmonies.<ref name=\"Nytimes\"/> The lyrics of \"Another Part of Me\" deal with being united, as \"we\".<ref name=\"Nytimes\"/> Critics Richard Cromelin (from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'')<ref name=\"latimes\"/> and Richard Harrington (from ''[[The Washington Post]]'') associated the song's lyrics with the [[Harmonic Convergence]] phenomenon that occurred around the time of the album's release, with Harrington highlighting the verse: \"The planets are lining up / We're bringing brighter days / They're all in line / Waiting for you / Can't you see? / You're just another part of me\".<ref>{{cite news|first= Richard |last= Harrington |title= Jackson's 'Bad' Looking Good |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= August 31, 1987 |accessdate= September 16, 2018 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/08/31/jacksons-bad-looking-good/f27fccc7-d322-4ad6-bce3-e0b37576a946/?noredirect=on}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Bad'' was described as \"the most anticipated album in history\".<ref name=\"Look Back\">{{cite news|title= A Look Back |newspaper= [[Miami Herald]] |url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12A99CBF149C2368&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date= June 26, 2009 |accessdate= February 18, 2010}}</ref> Regarding the album, [[Michael Goldberg (writer)|Michael Goldberg]] and David Handelman wrote for ''Rolling Stone'' that the release of the album was a \"major event\" and that \"If ''Bad'' sells \u201conly\u201d 10 million copies, that will be more than virtually any other record but could be viewed as a failure for Michael Jackson.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first1= Michael |last1= Goldberg |first2= David |last2= Handelman |title= Is Michael Jackson For Real? |magazine= Rolling Stone |date= September 24, 1987 |accessdate= October 14, 2019 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/is-michael-jackson-for-real-102872/}}</ref> \n\n''Bad'' was released on August 31, 1987.<ref name=\"Nytimes\">{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/31/arts/pop-michael-jackson-s-bad-follow-up-to-a-blockbuster.html |first= Jon |last= Pareles |authorlink= Jon Pareles |title= Pop: Michael Jackson's 'Bad,' Follow-Up to a Blockbuster |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= August 31, 1987 |accessdate= March 23, 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Campbell|1993|p=153}} It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"US\">{{cite magazine|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/1987-09-26/billboard-200 |title= Billboard 200 \u2013 Week of September 26, 1987 |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= September 26, 1987 |accessdate= March 23, 2015}}</ref> and remained there for six consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Keith |last= Caulfield |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/960801/taylor-swift-edges-susan-boyle-for-2009s-top-selling-album |title= Taylor Swift Edges Susan Boyle For 2009's Top-Selling Album |magazine= Billboard |date= January 6, 2010 |accessdate= March 23, 2015}}</ref> It remained in the top five on the ''Billboard'' 200 for 38 weeks, setting a record for the longest run in the top five by an album from a male solo artist.<ref>{{cite web|first= Ryan |last= Book |title= 9 Longest Streaks in Billboard 200 Top 5: Taylor Swift, Michael Jackson, Garth Brooks and More |website= Music Times |date= April 17, 2015 |accessdate= February 10, 2019 |url= https://www.musictimes.com/articles/36112/20150417/9-longest-streaks-billboard-200-top-5-taylor-swift-michael-jackson-garth-brooks.htm}}</ref> It was certified Diamond for shipping ten million copies in the US alone.<ref>{{cite news|title= Michael Jackson's \"Thriller\" Certified 33x Platinum; \"Bad\" Now Diamond |newspaper= Headline Planet |date= February 16, 2017 |accessdate= February 16, 2017 |url= http://headlineplanet.com/home/2017/02/16/michael-jacksons-thriller-certified-33x-platinum-bad-now-diamond/}}</ref> Though Jackson furthered his stance as a global pop superstar, in the US, ''Bad'' failed to match the sales of ''Thriller'', causing some in the media to label the album a \"disappointment\".<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/><ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite news|first= Jayson |last= Rodriguez |title= Michael Jackson's Musical Legacy, From the Jackson 5 to Invincible |publisher= MTV |date= June 25, 2009 |accessdate= February 8, 2010 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1614758/michael-jacksons-musical-legacy-from-the-jackson-5-to-invincible/}}</ref> \n\nIn the UK, ''Bad'' debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], selling 500,000 copies in its first five days.<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url= http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title= Certified Awards |publisher= [[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate= February 8, 2010}}</ref> ''Bad'' peaked at number one in 25 countries in total<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Michael Jackson Feted As Top Artist Of Decade After Selling 110 Million Discs |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=3L0DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60 |date= March 12, 1990 |page= 60 |volume= 77 |issue= 22 |issn= 0021-5996}}</ref> including Austria,<ref name=\"AUS\"/> Canada,<ref name=\"Canada\"/> Japan,<ref name=\"Japan\"/> New Zealand,<ref name=\"NZ\"/> Norway,<ref name=\"NOR\"/> Sweden,<ref name=\"SWE\"/> Switzerland<ref name=\"SWI\"/> and the UK.<ref name=\"UK\"/> It also charted at No. 13 in Mexico<ref name=\"MEX\"/> and at No. 22 in Portugal.<ref name=\"PT\"/> ''Bad'' has received various certifications worldwide. In the UK, the album is certified 13 times platinum with sales of 3.9 million, making it Jackson's second best-selling album there.<ref name=\"BPI\"/> ''Bad'' was certified seven times platinum for the shipment of over 700,000 copies in Canada by the [[Music Canada|Canadian Recording Industry Association]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Gold/Platinum |publisher= [[Music Canada]] |url= https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?fwp_gp_search=%22Bad%22%20%22Michael+Jackson%22 |accessdate= May 27, 2014}}</ref> In Europe, the 2001 reissue was certified platinum by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) for the sales of one million units.<ref>{{cite web|title= Michael Jackson: Albumi |publisher= International Federation of the Phonographic Industry |url= http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/artistit/michael+jackson |accessdate= February 8, 2010 |archivedate= August 4, 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160804022748/http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/artistit/Michael+Jackson |url-status= dead |language= fi}}</ref> The album was also certified platinum by the IFPI for the shipment of over 20,000 copies in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ifpihk.org/gold-disc-award-presented/1988 |title= Hong Kong sales certification |year= 1988 |publisher= IFPI Hong Kong |accessdate= February 8, 2014}}</ref> \n\n''Bad'' sold 7 million copies worldwide in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|first1= Charles |last1= Stockdale |first2= John |last2= Harrington |first3= Colman |last3= Andrews |title= 100 Best Pop Albums of All Time |website= 24/7 Wall St. |date= April 10, 2019 |accessdate= October 13, 2019 |url= https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/04/10/100-best-pop-albums-of-all-time-2/}}</ref> After a year, it had increased to 18 million copies.<ref>{{cite news|first= Richard |last= Harrington |title= Prince Michael Jackson Two Paths to the Top of Pop |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= October 9, 1988 |accessdate= October 14, 2019 |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/1988/10/09/prince-michael-jackson-two-paths-to-the-top-of-pop/4ff69a1b-e67c-4f54-8d98-58be1453867f/}}</ref> By 1989, it had become the world's second-best-selling album, behind ''Thriller'', having sold 22 million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"Report\">{{cite AV media|title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Entertainment Tonight December 1989 (TV Report) |date= December 29, 1989 |accessdate= November 7, 2019 |time= 2:40 |publisher= YouTube |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TW625VFj8gU&t=2m40s}}</ref> It was also the best-selling album worldwide of 1988 and 1989.<ref>{{cite AV media|title= Michael Jackson accepts AMA's Award of Achievement in 1989 (Part II) |time= 5:18 |date= January 30, 1989 |accessdate= November 28, 2019 |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vsifCQEFoNg&t=5m18s}}</ref> Globally, ''Bad'' is Jackson's second best-selling album behind ''Thriller'', with sales of over 35 million copies.<ref>{{cite news|first= Tom |last= Stevens |title= Michael Jackson's Bad at 30: share your favourite albums of 1987 |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= August 14, 2017 |accessdate= December 8, 2019 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/aug/14/michael-jacksons-bad-at-30-share-your-favourite-albums-of-1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Gil |last= Kaufman |title= Michael Jackson's New Album Cover Decoded |publisher= [[MTV]] |date= November 5, 2010 |accessdate= December 8, 2019 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651633/michael-jacksons-new-album-cover-decoded.jhtml}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n{{Main|Moonwalker|Bad (tour)}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F079012-0029, Berlin, Michael Jackson-Konzert, Wartende.jpg|thumb|Fans in [[Berlin]] lining up for the [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] tour concert on June 19, 1988]]\nThe marketing strategy for ''Bad'' was modeled on that for ''Thriller''.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite magazine|first1= Andrew |last1= Unterberger |first2= Ed |last2= Christman |title= How Michael Jackson's 'Bad' Became the First Album to Notch Five Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s |website= Billboard |date= August 31, 2017 |accessdate= December 19, 2018 |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7948954/michael-jackson-bad-hot-100-five-number-one-hits}}</ref> Similarly to the first ''Thriller'' single, \"[[The Girl Is Mine]]\", the first ''Bad'' single, \"I Just Can't Stop Loving You\", was a ballad duet, followed by two \"more obvious modern pop knockouts\" backed by music videos.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nA commemorative special on Jackson's life, ''The Magic Returns'', aired on [[CBS]] during prime time on the day of the release of ''Bad''. At the end of the documentary, the channel debuted the short film for \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\", directed by [[Martin Scorsese]] and featuring [[Wesley Snipes]].<ref name=\"Nytimes\"/> The marketing strategy, mastered by Frank DiLeo among others, also included Jackson producing another mini-movie around the time of the [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] world tour. That film, ''[[Moonwalker]]'' (1988), included performances of songs from ''Bad'', including \"[[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]]\", \"[[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\", \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" and \"[[Smooth Criminal]]\", the latter two released as sole videos at the end of the film.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Review: 'Moonwalker' |date= December 31, 1987 |url= https://variety.com/1987/film/reviews/moonwalker-1200427521/ |magazine= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate= January 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Dennis |last= Hunt |newspaper= Los Angeles Times |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-10/entertainment/ca-310_1_music-videos |title= VIDEO REVIEW : 'Moonwalker': A Stroll Through a Super Ego |date= January 10, 1989 |accessdate= January 25, 2010}}</ref> The film also included the music video for \"[[Come Together (Michael Jackson song)|Come Together]]\", with the song featuring seven years later on ''[[HIStory: Past, Present and Future, Book I]]''. It became the best-selling [[home video]] of all time.<ref name=\"Report\"/>\n\nSponsored by [[Pepsi]], the [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] tour began in Japan, marking Jackson's first performances there since 1972 with [[the Jackson 5]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Michael Jackson's new tour to start in Japan |newspaper= [[Manila Standard]] |date= July 2, 1987 |accessdate= October 24, 2019 |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=G2cVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QwsEAAAAIBAJ}}</ref>{{sfn|Campbell|1993|p=186}} Attendance figures for the first 14 dates in Japan totalled a record-breaking 450,000.{{sfn|Campbell|1993|p=208}} Jackson performed seven sold out shows at [[Wembley Stadium]], beating the previous record held by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Bruce Springsteen]] and [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]. The third concert on July 16, 1988 was attended by [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] and [[Prince Charles]].{{sfn|Campbell|1993|p=217}} Jackson was entered into the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' three times from the tour alone. The Bad tour was a major financial success, grossing $125 million.{{sfn|Brooks|2002|p=81}}{{sfn|Grant|2009|pp=104\u2013105}} He performed 132 concerts in 15 countries to an audience of 4.4 million.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Michael's Last Tour |magazine= [[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |date= April 1989 |volume= 44 |issue= 6 |pages= 142\u2013153 |issn= 0012-9011 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FtUDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA142}}</ref> \n\n==Singles==\n[[File:Michael Jackson-3.jpg|alt=A male with black hair singing into a microphone. The male is wearing a blue jacket and a white shirt with black pants and a white belt.|thumb|upright|Jackson performing \"[[The Way You Make Me Feel]]\" during the Bad tour in 1988]]\n\"I Just Can't Stop Loving You\", a duet with [[Siedah Garrett]], was the lead single. It peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and also reached number one in Belgium, Canada, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, the UK and Zimbabwe. \n\n\"Bad\" reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and remained there for two weeks, becoming the album's second number-one single, and Jackson's eighth number one entry on the chart. It also peaked at number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot R&B Singles]], [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] and [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] chart. Internationally, the song was also commercially successful, charting at the top of the charts in seven other countries including Ireland, Italy, Norway, Spain, and the Netherlands. The song was noted for introducing Jackson's edgy image.<ref>{{cite web|title= From the Record Crate: Michael Jackson \u2013 \"Bad\" (1987) |website= The Young Folks |date= August 31, 2017 |accessdate= November 6, 2019 |url= https://www.theyoungfolks.com/review/108840/from-the-record-crate-michael-jackson-bad-1987/}}</ref>\n\n\"The Way You Make Me Feel\" was the third consecutive ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number one hit and also hit number one in Ireland and Spain. Jackson performed the song at the [[30th Annual Grammy Awards|1988 Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite news|title= Jackson, Prince lose out at 30th Grammy Awards |url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MN&p_theme=mn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EFE485A92316866&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |newspaper= [[Star Tribune]] |date= March 3, 1988 |accessdate= March 3, 2010}}</ref> The last performance of the song was at the [[Michael Jackson: 30th Anniversary Special]] in at [[Madison Square Garden]] on September 7 and 10, 2001, where he performed the song with [[Britney Spears]].\n\n\"Man in the Mirror\" charted at number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot 100. It hit number one in Canada and Italy too. Jackson also performed the song at the 1988 Grammy Awards.<ref name=\"grammy\"/> It was nominated for [[Record of the Year]] at the next year's [[31st Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]].\n\n\"Dirty Diana\" was the record-breaking fifth ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one single from ''Bad''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1988-07-02 |title= The Hot 100 \u2013 Week of July 2, 1988 |magazine= Billboard |date= July 2, 1988 |accessdate= March 23, 2015}}</ref> Before the start of the Wembley Stadium show during the Bad tour in 1988, [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], who was in attendance, informed Jackson that it was one of her personal favorite songs{{sfn|Jones|2005|p=226}}\n\n\"Another Part of Me\" achieved less success, reaching number 11 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, but topped the [[R&B singles chart|R&B Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/bad-mw0000650293/awards |title= Bad \u2013 Awards |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= March 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1988-09-10 |title= The Hot 100 \u2013 September 10, 1988 |magazine= Billboard |date= July 2, 1988 |accessdate= March 23, 2015}}</ref> Like Jackson's earlier songs in his career such as \"[[Can You Feel It (The Jacksons song)|Can You Feel It]]\" and \"[[We Are the World]]\", the lyrics of the song emphasize global unity, love and outreach.\n\n\"Smooth Criminal\" became the sixth top 10 single on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, peaking at number seven.<ref name=\"awards\"/> The song reached number one in Belgium, Iceland, the Netherlands and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Smooth Criminal |url= http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/757/Michael-Jackson-Smooth-Criminal |publisher= Ultratop. Hung Medien |accessdate= March 23, 2015 |language= nl}}</ref> Though it was not one of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number-one singles, in retrospective reviews it has been regarded as one of the best songs on ''Bad'' and one of Jackson's [[signature song]]s.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= 50 Best Michael Jackson Songs |magazine= Rolling Stone |date= June 23, 2014 |accessdate= November 7, 2019 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/50-best-michael-jackson-songs-22188/}}</ref>\n\nReleased outside the United States and Canada, \"Leave Me Alone\" topped the Irish charts<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |title= The Irish Charts \u2013 All there is to know |publisher= Irishcharts.ie |accessdate= March 26, 2014}}</ref> and reached the top ten in five other countries.<ref>{{cite web|title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Leave Me Alone |url= http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/78a/Michael-Jackson-Leave-Me-Alone |publisher= Ultratop. Hung Medien |accessdate= March 23, 2015 |language= nl}}</ref> \"Leave Me Alone\" was Jackson's response to negative and exaggerated rumors about Jackson that frequently appeared in the [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloids]] post-1985 after the success of ''Thriller.''<ref>{{cite news|first= Sarah |last= Rodman |title= Michael Jackson, pop's uneasy king, dead at 50 |newspaper= [[The Boston Globe]] |date= June 26, 2009 |accessdate= November 6, 2019 |url= http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2009/06/26/michael_jackson_pop_icon_dead_at_50/?page=2}}</ref> The music video was the recipient of Best Music Video at the [[32nd Annual Grammy Awards|1990 Grammy Awards]].\n\nThe album's final single, \"Liberian Girl\", did not chart on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, but reached the top 20 in various countries and reached number one in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Jackson \u2013 Liberian Girl |url= http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/7c7/Michael-Jackson-Liberian-Girl |publisher= Ultratop. Hung Medien |accessdate= November 7, 2019 |language= nl}}</ref> The song has been sampled and covered by various artists including [[Chico Freeman]], [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] and [[MC Lyte]].<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Brian |last= Josephs |title= The Best Michael Jackson Samples |magazine= [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date= August 29, 2018 |accessdate= November 6, 2019 |url= https://www.complex.com/music/2018/08/the-best-michael-jackson-samples/}}</ref>\n\n''Bad'' became the first album to have five consecutive singles peak at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. In 2011, the record was tied by American singer [[Katy Perry]]'s ''[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry album)|Teenage Dream]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Gary |last= Trust |title= Katy Perry Makes Hot 100 History: Ties Michael Jackson's Record |magazine= Billboard |date= August 17, 2011 |accessdate= June 26, 2017 |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/467879/katy-perry-makes-hot-100-history-ties-michael-jacksons-record}}</ref> In the UK, seven of the ''Bad'' singles reached the UK top ten which was a record for any studio album for over 20 years.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= David |last= Renshaw |title= Calvin Harris' album '18 Months' beats Michael Jackson's chart record |magazine= NME |date= April 23, 2013 |accessdate= July 13, 2019 |url= https://www.nme.com/news/music/calvin-harris-43-1248274}}</ref>\n\n===Covers===\nIn 1988, [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] recorded \"[[Fat (song)|Fat]]\", a parody of \"Bad\", which won a Grammy Award for [[Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video|Best Concept Music Video]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Michael Jackson Remembered: 'Weird Al' Yankovic on Imitation as Flattery |magazine= Rolling Stone |date= July 9, 2009 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/michael-jackson-remembered-weird-al-yankovic-on-imitation-as-flattery-96288/}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| AOTY       = 84/100<ref>{{cite web|title= Michael Jackson \u2013 Bad |website= [[Album of the Year (website)|Album of the Year]] |accessdate= March 27, 2020 |url= https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/10686-michael-jackson-bad.php}}</ref>\n| rev1       = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score  = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n| rev2       = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Michael Jackson: Bad |magazine= [[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |url= http://www.blender.com:80/guide/back-catalogue/54453/bad.html |date= April 2007 |accessdate= October 3, 2018 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090722190018/http://www.blender.com/guide/back-catalogue/54453/bad.html |archivedate= July 22, 2009}}</ref>\n| rev3       = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score  = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|first= Colin |last= Larkin |authorlink= Colin Larkin (writer) |year= 2011 |title= [[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]] |edition= 5th concise |chapter= Jackson, Michael |publisher= [[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]] |isbn= 0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev4       = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score  = B+<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Leah |last= Greenblatt |title= Michael Jackson's albums |date= July 3, 2009 |magazine= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate= October 16, 2016 |url= http://www.ew.com/article/2009/07/03/michael-jacksons-albums}}</ref>\n| rev5       = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score  = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|first= Richard |last= Cromelin |date= December 13, 1987 |title= Unsilent Nights. . . : Four Stars Being Best, a Guide to the Top 40 |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate= October 16, 2016 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-13/entertainment/ca-28831_1_crazy-nights}}</ref>\n| rev6       = ''[[MusicHound]] R&B''\n| rev6Score  = 3.5/5<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first= Gary |editor1-last= Graff |editorlink1= Gary Graff |editor2-first= Josh Freedom |editor2-last= du Lac |editor3-first= Jim |editor3-last= McFarlin |year= 1998 |title= MusicHound R&B: The Essential Album Guide |chapter= Michael Jackson |publisher= [[Visible Ink Press]] |isbn= 1-5785-9026-4 |url= https://archive.org/details/musichoundrbesse00graf}}</ref>\n| rev7       = ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''\n| rev7Score  = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news|first= Ken |last= Tucker |authorlink= Ken Tucker |date= September 6, 1987 |title= Michael Jackson's adventurous mode |newspaper= [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]}}</ref>\n| rev8       = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/>\n| rev9       = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score  = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|first= Jon |last= Pareles |year= 2004 |title= [[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |pages= [https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/414 414\u201315] |editor1-first= Nathan |editor1-last= Brackett |editor2-first= Christian |editor2-last= Hoard |chapter= Michael Jackson |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster]] |edition= 4th |isbn= 0-7432-0169-8 |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA414 |accessdate= October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev10      = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = B+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |authorlink= Robert Christgau |title= Consumer Guide |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |date= September 29, 1987 |accessdate= October 16, 2016 |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv9b-87.php}}</ref>\n}}\nWhile ''Bad'' failed to match the critical success of ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller'', the album received widely positive reviews. Some critics highlighted aspects of the album as being superior to ''Thriller''. Davitt Sigerson from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that \"even without a milestone recording like '[[Billie Jean]]', ''Bad'' is still a better record than ''Thriller''.\" He believed the [[Filler (media)|filler]], such as \"[[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]]\", \"[[Dirty Diana]]\" and \"[[Liberian Girl]]\", made ''Bad'' \"richer, sexier and better than ''Thriller's'' forgettables.\"<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> In a contemporary review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Jon Pareles]] called ''Bad'' \"a well-made, catchy dance record by an enigmatic pop star\". He said while nothing on the record compared to \"Wanna Be Startin' Somethin'\", the music's \"concocted synthesizer-driven arrangements\" were \"clear\" and carried \"a solid kick\".<ref name=\"Nytimes\"/> In ''[[USA Today]]'', [[Edna Gundersen]] called it Jackson's \"most polished effort to date,\" that is \"calculated but not sterile.\"<ref>{{cite news|first= Edna |last= Gundersen |title= The ever-changing Jackson, Michael jumps back and he's super `Bad' |newspaper= [[USA Today]] |date= August 31, 1987}}</ref>\n\n[[Robert Christgau]] was also critical in ''[[The Village Voice]]''. He said its \"studio mastery\", along with Jackson's \"rhythmic and vocal power\", had made for \"the strongest and most consistent black pop album in years\", but lamented its lack of \"genius\" in the vein of \"Beat It\" or \"Billie Jean\" and panned the underlying themes in Jackson's lyrics. \"He's against burglary, speeding, and sex ('Dirty Diana' is as misogynistic as any piece of metal suck-my-cock), in favor of harmonic convergence and changing the world by changing the man in the mirror. His ideal African comes from Liberia. And he claims moonwalking makes him a righteous brother. Like shit.\"\n\n''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' commented that while ''Bad'' was another worldwide commercial success, the album \"inevitably failed to match the success of ''Thriller'' despite Jackson's massive and grueling world tour\".<ref>{{cite news|title= Video: Michael Jackson's weird and wonderful life |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph |date= June 26, 2009 |accessdate= February 19, 2010 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/celebrity-obituaries/5643156/Michael-Jackson.html}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' commented that \"the best way to view\" ''Bad'' was not as \"the sequel to ''Thriller''.<ref name=\"Sigerson\"/> Richard Harrington of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' felt that while the album could not live up to post-''Thriller'' expectations, it would be \"considerably fairer to compare\" ''Bad'' with ''Off the Wall''. His overall opinion on ''Bad'' was that it was \"a very good record\" that is \"immaculately produced and with some scintillating vocal performances from Jackson\".<ref>{{cite news|first= Richard |last= Harrington |title= Article: Jackson's `Bad': Looking Good; Not a `Thriller' but It's Full of Flash |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1340706.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121103023855/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1340706.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= November 3, 2012 |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |publisher= [[HighBeam Research]] |date= August 31, 1987 |accessdate= February 7, 2010}}</ref> Richard Cromelin of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called ''Bad'' \"a fair-to-strong array of [[Soul music|soul]] and rock blends\", commenting that the record was \"not bad\" and was more \"reminiscent of ''Off the Wall''{{'}}s uniform strength than ''Thriller''{{'}}s peaks and valleys\". Cromelin felt that it would be \"disappointing\" if this album's \"creative level\" is where Jackson wants to stay.<ref name=\"Latimes\"/>\n\nIn 1988, ''Bad'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance \u2013 Male]], [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance \u2013 Male]], and won for [[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Recording \u2013 Non Classical]].<ref name=\"Grammy 1988\">{{cite web|url= http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1988/grammys.htm |title= 30th Grammy Awards \u2013 1988 |publisher= Rock On The Net |accessdate= February 8, 2010}}</ref> The following year, it was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] for \"Man in the Mirror\",<ref name=\"Grammy 1989\">{{cite web|url= http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1989/grammys.htm |title= 30th Grammy Awards \u2013 1989 |publisher= Rock On The Net |accessdate= February 8, 2010}}</ref> and in 1990 won for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video \u2013 Short Form]] (for \"Leave Me Alone\").<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1990/grammys.htm |title= 32nd Grammy Awards \u2013 1990 |publisher= Rock On The Net |accessdate= February 8, 2010}}</ref> At the [[1988 Soul Train Music Awards]], the album won [[Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul Album \u2013 Male|Best R&B/Soul Album \u2013 Male]] and \"Bad\" won [[Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul Single \u2013 Male|Best R&B/Soul Single \u2013 Male]]. The following year, \"Man in the Mirror\" also won Best R&B/Soul Single \u2013 Male. At the [[1989 Brit Awards]], \"Smooth Criminal\" won [[Brit Award for British Video of the Year|British Video of the Year]]. At the 1989 [[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], ''Bad'' won [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Album of the Year]].<ref name=\"Zimbio\">{{cite web|title= 1989: George Michael vs. Michael Jackson |website= Zimbio |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.zimbio.com/Album+of+the+Year+-+Billboard+vs.+Grammy/articles/MBWTNDsiNKX/1989+George+Michael+vs+Michael+Jackson}}</ref> Following the appraisal of the music videos of the singles from ''Bad,'' along with his previous music videos throughout the 1980s, Jackson was awarded the [[Michael Jackson Video Vanguard Award|MTV Video Vanguard Artist of the Decade Award]].<ref>{{cite book|first= J. Randy |last= Taraborrelli |year= 2009 |title= Michael Jackson: The Magic, the Madness, the Whole Story |publisher= Pan Books |isbn= 978-0-330-51565-8 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7EkwuCFnE28C&pg=PT308}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and influence==\n===Retrospective assessments===\n[[File:Michael Jackson.jpg|alt=|thumb|227x227px|Jackson's ''Bad'' era wax figure at [[Madame Tussauds]]]]''Bad'' has been credited as defining the sound of \"late-80s' pop\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Zach |last= Schonfeld |title= Michael Jackson's 'Bad' at 30: Every song, ranked from best to worst |magazine= [[Newsweek]] |date= August 31, 2017 |accessdate= November 15, 2019 |url= https://www.newsweek.com/michael-jackson-bad-video-smooth-criminal-king-pop-657221}}</ref> and redefining the sound of pop music.<ref>{{cite web|first= David |last= Bennun |title= How Michael Jackson's Bad Shaped Pop As We Know It |website= [[The Quietus]] |date= August 21, 2017 |accessdate= November 17, 2019 |url= https://thequietus.com/articles/23033-michael-jackson-bad-review-anniversary}}</ref> It also further set the standard for innovation in music videos following the success of the music videos for \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\", \"[[Smooth Criminal]]\", \"[[The Way You Make Me Feel]]\" and \"[[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\".<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> A writer for the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' reflected back on the anticipation for ''Bad'', describing the album's release as being the \"most hotly anticipated album in history\".<ref name=\"Look Back\"/> In a retrospective review for [[BBC Music]], Mike Diver regarded ''Bad'' as a landmark factor of [[1980s#Popular culture|1980s pop culture]]: \"A multi-million-unit-shifter, ''Bad'' was (and remains) as important to 1980s pop culture as the rise of the [[Walkman]], the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|Back to the Future]] movies, and [[Who shot J.R.?|the shooting of JR]]. Like 1982\u2019s ''Thriller'', it\u2019s an album that appeared to easily find a home within the record collection of rockers and poppers, punks and poets alike.\" Diver also praised the album for being the \"best of the best [of its time]\" and an \"essential pop masterpiece\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Mike |last= Diver |title= Michael Jackson Bad 25 Review |publisher= [[BBC Music]] |year= 2012 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gxb6/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[VH1]] said of the album:{{quote|Understandably, the expectations for the album were ridiculously high, and grew even higher after Jackson planned duets with the likes of Prince (on the title track) and Whitney Houston (and Aretha Franklin and Barbra Streisand). None of those collaborations ended up happening, but they only increased the hype for the album. ''Bad'' was a deeply personal project for Jackson \u2013 he wrote nine of the 11 songs \u2013 one that saw him gain further independence and debut a harder-edged look and sound.<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/>}}[[File:Michael Jackson's \"Bad\" Jacket and Belt.jpg|thumb|alt=A black jacket with five round golden medals on its left and right shoulder and a gold ban on its left arm sleeve. The jacket has two belt straps on the right bottom sleeve. Underneath the jacket is a golden belt, with a round pendant in the center of it. There is a red light reflecting on the jacket and belt as well as a gold squared plat on the left side of the jacket and belt.|Jackson often wore a plated military styled jacket with a belt during the ''Bad'' era to give himself an edgier look.<ref name=\"otherinfo\"/>|link=File:Michael Jackson's \"Bad\" Jacket and Belt.jpg|left|204x204px]]In 2009, Jim Farber of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' wrote that ''Bad'' \"streamlined the quirks\" of Jackson's two previous albums to \"create his most smooth work of pop to date.\"<ref>{{cite news|first= Jim |last= Farber |title= For Michael Jackson, the beat went on: after 'Thriller,' hits kept coming |newspaper= [[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date= June 26, 2009 |accessdate= March 23, 2015 |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/michael-jackson-beat-thriller-hits-coming-article-1.373272}}</ref> [[Joseph Vogel]] was also enthusiastic about the record. \"On ''Bad'', Jackson's music is largely about creating moods, visceral emotions, and fantastical scenarios....[with] each song work[ing] as a dream capsule, inviting the listener into a vivid new sound, story, space.\" He called ''Bad'' \"a compelling, phantasmagorical album, which a handful of critics recognized from the beginning.\"<ref>{{cite book|first= Joseph |last= Vogel |authorlink= Joseph Vogel |year= 2012 |title= Man in the Music: The Creative Life and Work of Michael Jackson |url= https://archive.org/details/maninmusiccreati0000voge |url-access= registration |page= [https://archive.org/details/maninmusiccreati0000voge/page/114 114] |location= New York |publisher= [[Sterling Publishing|Sterling]] |isbn= 978-1-40277-938-1}}</ref> According to Jayson Rodriguez of [[MTV]], \"following the twin cannons that were ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller'' wouldn't be an easy task for most, but Jackson's follow-up, 1987's ''Bad'', was formidable by all accounts.\"<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Rodriguez also felt that ''Bad''  was \"wrongfully dismissed by critics because it wasn't the sales blockbuster that ''Thriller'' was\" and that during the ''Bad'' era, Jackson's vocal hiccups and stammered \"shamone\" would become staples in his music that were \"heightening and highlighting the emotion of his lyrics.\"<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Erika Ramirez of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' highlighted \"[[Another Part of Me]]\" and \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" for showcasing Jackson as a \"caring humanitarian\" and emphasizing world unity. According to Edward M. Litwin of ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', ''Bad'' is a \"far more exciting album than [''Thriller''] because it\u2019s not only a cohesive album, but it also represents Jackson's greatest and most experimental foray into rock\". Litwin also found that the album is Jackson's \"boldest, riskiest and most experimental work\".<ref>{{cite news|first= Edward M. |last= Litwin |title= 'Bad' Turns 30: Revisiting the King's Rockingest Album |newspaper= [[The Harvard Crimson]] |date= September 12, 2017 |accessdate= January 19, 2020 |url= https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2017/9/12/bad-retrospective/}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]'', Matthew Allen claimed that ''Bad'' was the start of Jackson's three-year \"prime\" in his \"vocals, songwriting, producing, performing and video output\". Allen also regarded the album as \"[doubling] down on the edge\" of ''Thriller'' in both subject matter and instrumental arrangement.<ref>{{cite web|first= Matthew |last= Allen |title= Michael Jackson's Bad: 30 Years Ago the King of Pop Hit His Prime ... so Why Is That Album Underrated? |work= [[The Root (magazine)|The Root]] |date= August 18, 2017 |accessdate= January 20, 2020 |url= https://www.theroot.com/michael-jackson-s-bad-30-years-ago-the-king-of-pop-hit-1797835413}}</ref> Writing for Albumism, Chris Lacy considered ''Bad'' possibly being superior to ''[[Off the Wall]]'' and ''Thriller:'' \"Comparisons with ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller'' are unimportant, except for this one: ''Bad'' is a pure pop masterpiece that stands parallel with\u2014and, at times, eclipses\u2014its classic predecessors.\" Lacy also stated that ''Bad'' set a \"new gold standard for pop music and entertainment\".<ref>{{cite web|first= Chris |last= Lacy |title= TRIBUTE: Celebrating 30 Years of Michael Jackson's 'Bad' |website= Albumism |date= August 29, 2017 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.albumism.com/features/tribute-celebrating-30-years-of-michael-jackson-bad}}</ref> Chaz Lipp of ''The Morton Report'' described ''Bad'' as a \"classic collection of sterling pop songs with enough hits that it almost plays like a \"best of\" collection\" and also regarded the album as Jackson's peak in songwriting. Lipp further praised ''Bad'' and Jackson for their \"unforgettable hooks\" and \"jaw-dropping\" vocals respectively.<ref>{{cite web|first= Chaz |last= Lipp |title= Music Review: Michael Jackson \u2013 ''Bad 25'' \u2013 25th Anniversary Edition (3-CD/1-DVD) |work= The Morton Report |date= September 16, 2012 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= http://www.themortonreport.com/entertainment/music/music-review-michael-jackson-bad-25-25th-anniversary-edition-3-cd1-dvd/}}</ref>\n\n===21st century appeal===\n25 years after its release, film director [[Spike Lee]] claimed that ''Bad'' sounds the 'freshest' today compared to other [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] number-one albums which were released in 1987, such as [[U2]]'s ''[[The Joshua Tree]]'', [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s ''[[Tunnel of Love (album)|Tunnel of Love]]'' and [[Whitney Houston]]'s ''[[Whitney (album)|Whitney]]'': \"Go to the charts ... and see what were the top albums 25 years ago, play those albums now and then play ''Bad'', and then see which one still sounds fresh and doesn't sound dated.\"<ref>{{cite news|first= Rob |last= Markman |title= Michael Jackson's ''Bad'': 25 Years Later, Does It Hold Up? |publisher= MTV |date= August 31, 2012 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1693013/michael-jackson-bad-25-years-later/}}</ref> Following the 30th anniversary of the album's release, Kendall Fisher of ''[[E! Online]]'' regarded it as having an impact on contemporary artists; \"Essentially, [''Bad''] epitomized the massive influence [Jackson] had on many of today's biggest artists.\"<ref>{{cite web|first= Kendall |last= Fisher |title= Michael Jackson's ''Bad'' Album Turns 30: How the King of Pop Influenced Today's Biggest Artists |website= [[E! Online]] |date= August 31, 2017 |accessdate= November 17, 2019 |url= https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/876918/michael-jackson-s-bad-album-turns-30-how-the-king-of-pop-influenced-today-s-biggest-artists}}</ref>\n\n[[Kanye West]] claimed that Jackson's outfit in the \"Bad\" video is \"far more influential\" than Jackson's outfit in the \"[[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Thriller]]\" video. West also said \"I almost dress like that [Jackson's outfit in the \"Bad\" video] today.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Kanye West, Chris Brown, & Mariah Carey Celebrate Michael Jackson's Legacy on 'Bad 25' Special |magazine= [[Rap-Up]] |date= November 23, 2012 |accessdate= January 20, 2020 |url= https://www.rap-up.com/2012/11/23/kanye-west-chris-brown-mariah-carey-celebrate-michael-jacksons-legacy-on-bad-25-special/}}</ref> [[Justin Bieber]] also cited \"The Way You Make Me Feel\" video as the \"basis\" for and how he \"pictured\" his \"[[Baby (Justin Bieber song)|Baby]]\" music video.<ref>{{cite AV media|title= Justin Bieber on Michael Jackson: BAD 25 |date= December 1, 2012 |accessdate= January 20, 2020 |publisher= [[YouTube]] |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c8RZJDC1p6E}}</ref> [[Ludacris]], who was featured on Bieber's \"Baby\", said that the video is \"like a 2010 version of Jackson's \"The Way You Make Me Feel\"\".<ref>{{cite news|first= Jocelyn |last= Vena |title= Justin Bieber Happy to Leave the Rapping to Ludacris |publisher= MTV |date= February 3, 2010 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1631145/20100203/bieber_justin.jhtml |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100206075341/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1631145/20100203/bieber_justin.jhtml |archivedate= February 6, 2010}}</ref> After the video was released in 2010, MTV regarded the video as \"the new version of \"The Way You Make Me Feel\"\" and also noted that the choreography \"does use a few of Jackson's less-suggestive moves.\"<ref>{{cite news|first= Jocelyn |last= Vena |title=Justin Bieber Bowls with Drake, Ludacris in 'Baby' Video |publisher= MTV |date= February 19, 2010 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |archivedate= March 15, 2010 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1632234/20100219/bieber_justin.jhtml |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100315073536/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1632234/20100219/bieber_justin.jhtml}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\nIn 2003, ''Bad'' was ranked number 202 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]],<ref name=\"500Albums\"/> and 203 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\"500 greatest\">{{cite magazine|title= 500 Greatest Albums of All Time |date= May 31, 2012 |accessdate= September 16, 2019 |magazine= [[Rolling Stone]] |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/michael-jackson-bad-160848/}}</ref> In ''[[NME]]''{{'}}s [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] list, ''Bad'' was ranked number 204.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite magazine|first= Emily |last= Barker |title= The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time: 300\u2013201 |magazine= NME |date= October 24, 2013 |accessdate= January 8, 2020 |url= https://www.nme.com/photos/the-500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-300-201-1426482}}</ref> It was also included in the book titled ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref name=\"1001 Series\"/> In 2009, [[VH1]] listed ''Bad'' at number 43 on their list of 100 Greatest Albums of All Time of the MTV Generation.<ref name=\"Album of All Time\"/> In 2012, ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' ranked the album at number 48 on its list of The 100 Best Albums of the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|title= The 100 Best Albums of the 1980s |work= [[Slant Magazine]] |date= March 5, 2012 |accessdate= August 15, 2012 |url= http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-albums-of-the-1980s/P11}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked ''Bad'' at number 138 on its list of the Greatest of All Time ''Billboard'' 200 Albums.<ref name=\"All Time\">{{cite web|title= Greatest of All Time Billboard 200 Albums |website= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate= November 12, 2015 |url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-billboard-200-albums |url-status= live |archivedate= October 1, 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161001122709/http://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-billboard-200-albums}}</ref> It was ranked number 30 in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s list of the Greatest of All Time R&B/Hip-Hop Albums, out of 100 albums.<ref>{{cite web|title= Greatest of All Time Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums |work= Billboard |accessdate= January 8, 2020 |url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-r-b-hip-hop-albums}}</ref> On ''Billboard''{{'}}s list of All 92 Diamond-Certified Albums Ranked From Worst to Best: Critic's Take, it was ranked number 41.<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Andrew |last= Unterberger |title= All 92 Diamond-Certified Albums Ranked From Worst to Best: Critic's Take |magazine= Billboard |date= September 29, 2016 |accessdate= January 24, 2020 |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/billboard-lists/7526410/diamond-certified-album-riaa-ranked}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Organization\n!style=\"width:100px;\"|Country\n!Accolade\n!Year\n!Source\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award]]s\n|United States\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Recording \u2013 Non-Classical]] \n|1988\n|<ref name=\"Grammy 1988\"/>\n|-\n|[[Billboard Music Award|''Billboard'' Music Awards]]\n|United States\n|[[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Album of the Year]]\n|1989\n|<ref name=\"Zimbio\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n|United States\n|Greatest of All Time ''Billboard'' 200 Albums (Ranked #138)\n|2015\n|<ref name=\"All Time\"/>\n|-\n|[[Quintessence Editions]]\n|United Kingdom\n|''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''\n|2003\n|<ref name=\"1001 Series\">{{cite web|url= http://www.1001beforeyoudie.com/qssUS/us_1001_albums.html |title= 1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151435/http://www.1001beforeyoudie.com/qssUS/us_1001_albums.html |archivedate= April 2, 2015}}. [[Quintessence Editions]] Ltd..</ref>\n|-\n|[[NME]]\n|United Kingdom\n|[[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] (Ranked #204)\n|2013\n|<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|United States\n|[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] (Ranked #203)\n|2012\n|<ref name=\"500Albums\">{{cite magazine|title= The RS 500 Greatest Albums of All Time (1\u2013500) |magazine= Rolling Stone |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5938174/the_rs_500_greatest_albums_of_all_time/3 |archivedate= January 15, 2007 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070115112104/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5938174/the_rs_500_greatest_albums_of_all_time/3}}</ref><ref name=\"500 greatest\"/>\n|-\n|[[VH1]]\n|United States\n|100 Greatest Albums of All Time of the MTV Generation (Ranked #43)\n|2009\n|<ref name=\"Album of All Time\">{{cite web|url= http://www.mtv.co.uk/channels/vh1/chart/greatest-albums-ever |title= VH1 \u2013 Greatest Albums Ever |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090310113440/http://www.mtv.co.uk/channels/vh1/chart/greatest-albums-ever |archivedate= March 10, 2009}}. MTV. Viacom.</ref>\n|}\n\n==''Bad 25''==\n{{Main|Bad 25}}\nIt was announced on May 3, 2012, that the Estate of Michael Jackson and Epic Records would be releasing a 25th anniversary album of ''Bad''. The album was named ''[[Bad 25]]'' and was released on September 18, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.michaeljackson.com/us/news/25th-anniversary-michael-jacksons-landmark-album-bad-celebrated-september-18-release-new-bad-25 |title= 25th Anniversary of Michael Jackson's Landmark Album Bad Celebrated with September 18 Release of New Bad 25 Packages |date= May 21, 2012 |accessdate= June 30, 2012 |publisher= [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. Michaeljackson.com}}</ref> Since the release of ''Bad 25'', there has been a discontinuation of the 2001 special edition.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks written by [[Michael Jackson]], except where noted; all tracks produced by [[Quincy Jones]] and co-produced by Jackson.\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = [[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]] (Writer Michael Jackson)\n| length1 = 4:08\n| title2 = [[The Way You Make Me Feel]] (Writer- Michael Jackson)\n| length2 = 4:59\n| title3 = [[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]] (Writer Michael Jackson)\n| length3 = 4:03\n| title4 = [[Liberian Girl]] (Writer Michael Jackson \n| length4 = 3:55\n| title5 = [[Just Good Friends (song)|Just Good Friends]]\n| note5 = with [[Stevie Wonder]]; writers: [[Terry Britten]], [[Graham Lyle]]\n| length5 = 4:09\n| title6 = [[Another Part of Me]]\n| length6 = 3:55\n| title7 = [[Man in the Mirror]]\n| note7 = writers: [[Siedah Garrett]], [[Glen Ballard]]\n| length7 = 5:21\n| title8 = [[I Just Can't Stop Loving You]]\n| note8 = with [[Siedah Garrett]] \n| length8 = 4:27\n| title9 = [[Dirty Diana]]\n| length9 = 4:42\n| title10 = [[Smooth Criminal]]\n| length10 = 4:20\n| all_writing = \n| title11 = [[Leave Me Alone (Michael Jackson song)|Leave Me Alone]]\n| length11 = 4:41\n| total_length = \n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 2001 special edition bonus tracks\n| collapsed       = yes\n\n| title12         = Quincy Jones Interview #1\n| length12        = 4:04\n\n| title13         = Streetwalker\n| length13        = 5:49\n\n| title14         = Quincy Jones Interview #2\n| length14        = 2:54\n\n| title15         = Todo Mi Amor Eres T\u00fa\n| note15          = with Garrett; writers: Jackson, [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]]\n| length15        = 4:05\n\n| title16         = Quincy Jones Interview #3\n| length16        = 2:31\n\n| title17         = Spoken Intro to Fly Away\n| length17        = 0:09\n\n| title18         = Fly Away\n| length18        = 3:27\n}}\n\n;Notes\nRe-issues of ''Bad'' feature a number of changes when compared to the original 1987 release:\n* \"Bad\" \u2013 The original mix was replaced with the 7\" single mix. The most notable difference is the lack of horns in all the choruses except for the last two. Horns are also missing from the second and third pre-choruses. The rhythm guitar during the choruses is also turned up along with the hi-hats.\n* \"The Way You Make Me Feel\" \u2013 The full-length remix used for the single with louder vocals and ad libs added to the end replaced the original album mix.\n* \"I Just Can't Stop Loving You\" omits Michael Jackson's spoken intro.\n* \"Dirty Diana\" is replaced with the single edit of the song.\n* \"Smooth Criminal\" went through two changes on the album. It was remixed to make the kick drum heavier and the bass synth fatter. The quick-sequenced synclavier behind the bass has been rendered mono as well. The first version of this mix left the breathing intact, but was later removed after some time.\n* \"Leave Me Alone\" was not included on the original vinyl nor cassette releases but was included on the CD release and now is included in all releases.\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel as listed in the album's [[liner notes]] are:<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n* Lead and backing vocals: [[Michael Jackson]]\n* Background vocals: [[Siedah Garrett]] (tracks 7\u20138), [[The Winans]] (7), and The [[Andra\u00e9 Crouch]] Choir (7)\n* Bass guitar: [[Nathan East]] (track 8)\n* [[Hammond organ]]: [[Jimmy Smith (musician)|Jimmy Smith]] (track 1)\n* Drums: [[John Robinson (drummer)|John Robinson]] (tracks 1\u20134, 9\u201310), Miko Brando (3), [[Ollie E. Brown]] (3, 5), [[Leon \"Ndugu\" Chancler]] (8), [[Bill Bottrell]] (10), Bruce Swedien (5, 10), Humberto Gatica (5)\n* [[programming (music)|Programming]]: Douglas Getschal (tracks 1\u20134, 9), Cornelius Mims (5), Larry Williams (11)\n* Guitar: [[David Williams (guitarist)|David Williams]] (tracks 1\u20133, 6, 9\u201310), Bill Bottrell (3), [[Eric Gale]] (2), Danny Hull, [[Steve Stevens]] (solo, 9), [[Dann Huff]] (7\u20138), [[Michael Landau]] (5), [[Paul Jackson Jr.]] (6, 9, 11)\n* Trumpet: Gary Grant, [[Jerry Hey]] (tracks 1\u20133, 5\u20136, 10)\n* Sounds engineered: Ken Caillat, and Tom Jones\n* Percussion: [[Paulinho da Costa]] (tracks 1\u20135, 8), Ollie E. Brown (2, 7)\n* Keyboards: Stefan Stefanovic, [[Greg Phillinganes]] (track 7)\n* Saxophone: Kim Hutchcroft (tracks 1\u20133, 5\u20136, 10), Larry Williams (1\u20132, 5\u20136, 10)\n* [[Synclavier]] (tracks 1\u20136, 8\u201310), digital guitar (1), finger snaps (2), sound effects (3): Christopher Currell\n* Synthesizer: John Barnes (tracks 1\u20134, 6, 9\u201310), [[Michael Boddicker]] (1\u20135, 9\u201310), Greg Phillinganes (1\u20133, 5, 8, 11, solo\u20131), Rhett Lawrence (5\u20136), [[David Paich]] (4, 8), Larry Williams (4\u20135, 11), Glen Ballard (7), [[Randy Kerber]] (7), [[Randy Waldman]] (9)\n* Piano: John Barnes (track 8), Kevin Maloney (10)\n* Rhythm arrangement: Michael Jackson (tracks 1\u20134, 6, 9\u201311), Quincy Jones (1, 3\u20135, 7\u20138), Christopher Currell (1), John Barnes (4, 6, 9\u201310), Graham Lyle (5), Terry Britten (5), [[Glen Ballard]] (7), Jerry Hey (9)\n* Horn arrangement: Jerry Hey (tracks 1\u20133, 5\u20136, 10)\n* Programming: Larry Williams (tracks 2), Eric Persing (3), [[Steve Porcaro]] (4, 8), Casey Young (11)\n* Midi saxophone: Larry Williams (track 3)\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1987\u20132015)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australian Albums ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992 |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, N.S.W.]] |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|1|artist=Michael Jackson|album=Bad|accessdate=March 23, 2015|refname=\"AUS\"}}\n|-\n|Brazilian Albums ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|ABPD]])<ref>{{cite web|title= ABPD CD \u2013 TOP 10 Semanal |publisher= [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos]] |url= http:/