African pianist, composer and teacher (1896\u20131987) \n*[[Adolph Heinrich Joseph Sutro]] mayor of San Francisco (1830\u20131898)\n*[[Adolph Jacobs]], American guitar player (1939\u20132014)\n*[[Adolph Joffe]], Russian-Jewish diplomat (1883\u20131927)\n*[[Adolph Johannes Brand]], South African pianist and composer (1934\u2013)\n*[[Adolph Kolping]], German priest (1813\u20131865)\n*[[Adolph Kukulowicz]], Canadian ice-hockey player (1933-2008)\n*[[Adolf Malan]], former South African rugby union footballer. (1961\u2013)\n*[[Adolph Malan]], South African [[flying ace]] in [[WW2]] (1910\u20131963)\n*Adolph Marx, birth name of American comic actor [[Harpo Marx]] (1888\u20131961)\n*[[Adolph Mongo]], American political strategist and commentator (1954\u2013)\n*[[Adolph M\u00fcller (Founder of Varta)]], (1852\u20131928) \n*[[Adolph Ochs]], American newspaper publisher (1858\u20131935)\n*[[Adolph L. Reed, Jr.]], professor of political science and writer (1947\u2013)\n*[[Adolph Rupp]], American college basketball coach (1901\u20131977)\n*[[Adolph \"Dolph\" Schayes]], American basketball player (1928\u20132015)\n*[[Adolph G. Schwenk]], American Marine general (1922\u20132004)\n*[[Adolph Tidemand]], Norwegian classical-romantic painter (1814\u20131876)\n*[[Adolph von Carlowitz]],  German army commander during the First World War (1858\u20131928)\n*[[Adolph P. Yushkevich]], Russian mathematician (1906\u20131993)\n*[[Adolph Zukor]],  Hungarian-Jewish American film mogul and founder of [[Paramount Pictures]] (1873\u20131976)\n* [[Hubert Blaine Wolfeschlegelsteinhausenbergerdorff Sr.]], American typesetter whose actual name starts with \"Adolph\" (1914\u20131997)\n\n=== Adolphe ===\n\n*[[Adolphe Adam]], French composer and music critic (1803\u20131856)\n*[[Adolphe Alexandre Chaillet]], Inventor of the Centennial Light (1867\u2013 1914)\n*[[Adolphe Cr\u00e9mieux]], French-Jewish lawyer and statesman (1796\u20131880)\n*[[Adolphe Goldschmidt]], German-Jewish co-inheritor of the Goldschmidt family bank (1838\u20131918)\n*[[Adolphe Guillaumat]], French Army general during World War I (1863-1940)\n*[[Adolphe Max]], Belgian politician and mayor of Brussels (1869\u20131939)\n*[[Adolphe Menjou]], American actor and anti-Communist activist (1890\u20131963)\n*[[Adolphe Nourrit]], French opera singer (1802\u20131839)\n*[[Adolphe Sax]], Belgian musician and inventor of the saxophone (1814\u20131894)\n*[[Adolphe Thiers]], French Prime Minister, President, and historian (1797\u20131877)\n*[[Adolphe L\u00e9on Willette]], French painter and architect of the Moulin Rouge (1857\u20131926)\n\n=== Adolphus ===\n\n*Adolphus Anthony Cheatham ([[Doc Cheatham]]), American jazz trumpeter, singer, and bandleader (1905\u20131997)\n*[[Adolphus Busch]], American businessman and co-founder of Anheuser-Busch (1839\u20131913)\n*[[Dolph Sweet|Adolphus Jean Sweet]], American actor (1920\u20131985)\n*[[Adolphus W. Green]], American businessman, founder of Nabisco (1844\u20131917)\n*[[Adolphus Warburton Moore]] (A. W. Moore), British civil servant and mountaineer (1841\u20131887)\n\n==People with the surname Adolf or Adolphus==\n*[[Helen Adolf]], Austrian\u2013American linguist and literature scholar. (1895 \u2013 1998)\n*[[John Adolphus]], English historian (1768\u20131845)\n*[[John Leycester Adolphus]], English lawyer, jurist and author (1795\u20131862)\n\n==Fictional characters==\n*Adolphus Cusins, a character in ''[[Major Barbara]]'' by [[George Bernard Shaw]]\n*Dolph Starbeam, a character in the animated sitcom ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n*Dolph, an antagonist on the animated series ''[[Alfred Jodocus Kwak]]''\n*Adolf Kamil and Adolf Kaufmann, title characters of the manga ''[[Adolf (manga)|Adolf]]'' by Osamu Tezuka\n*Saint Adolphus, a character in [[Ken Follett]]'s ''[[The Pillars of the Earth]]''\n*Adolf Verloc, a character in [[Joseph Conrad]]\u2019s ''[[The Secret Agent]]''\n*Adolf K. Weismann, also known as [[List of K characters#Yashiro Isana|Yashiro Isana]], is the main protagonist in the anime series ''K''\n\n==See also==\n*[[\u00c6thelwulf (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ataulf]]\n*[[Adolff]]\n*[[Adolphine (name)|Adolphine]], the female equivalent of the name Adolf\n*[[Dolf (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Dolph (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Ludolph]]\n*[[Rudolph (name)|Rudolph]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name|type=both}}\n\n[[Category:German masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Dutch masculine given names]]\n[[Category:English masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Norwegian masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Swedish masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Finnish masculine given names]]\n[[Category:French masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Danish masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Icelandic masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Swiss masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Masculine given names]]\n[[Category:Connotation]]\n[[Category:Adolf Hitler]]\n", "name_user": "ExRat", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolf"}
{"title_page": "Quranic createdness", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|Theological doctrine}}\n\n{{Quran}}\n'''Createdness''' refers to the Islamic doctrinal position that the [[Qur\u2019an]] was created, rather than having always existed and thus being \"uncreated\". In the Muslim world the opposite point of view \u2014 that the Quran is uncreated \u2014 is the accepted stance among the majority [[Sunni]] Muslims while minority sects [[Shia]] [[Twelver]]s and [[Zaydi]], and the [[Kharijite]]s believe the Quran is created.<ref name=\"Glass\u00e9-268\">{{cite book|last1=Glass\u00e9|first1=Cyril|last2=Smith|first2=Huston|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2002|publisher=Rowman Altamira.|page=268|edition=revised, reprinted|url=https://books.google.com/?id=focLrox-frUC&pg=PA268&dq=Uncreatedness+of+the+Quran#v=onepage&q=Uncreatedness%20of%20the%20Quran&f=false|accessdate=7 September 2015|isbn=9780759101906}}</ref> \n\nThe dispute over which was true became a significant point of contention in early Islam. The Islamic rationalist philosophical school known as the [[Mu'tazila]] held that if the Quran is God's word, logically God \"must have preceded his own speech\".<ref name=SKHE-77>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Heaven+on+Earth:+A+Journey+Through+Shari%27a+Law#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20on%20Earth%3A%20A%20Journey%20Through%20Shari'a%20Law&f=false}}</ref> The Qur'an, of course, expresses God's eternal will, but the work itself must have been created by Him at some point in time.<ref name=\"OISO\">{{cite web |title=Qur'an |url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/article/opr/t243/e275 |website=Oxford Islamic Studies Online |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nTraditionists, on the other hand, held that numerous  records of the words, actions, or approval of Muhammad (''[[a\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth]]'') support the contention that as God's speech, the Qur\u2019an is an attribute of God and therefore \"uncreated\".<ref name=\"islamQA-created\">{{cite web |last1=Saalih al-Munajjid |first1=Muhammad |title=The Qur'an is the word of Allah, may He be exalted, and is not created. 227441 |url=https://islamqa.info/en/answers/227441/the-quran-is-the-word-of-allah-may-he-be-exalted-and-is-not-created |website=Islam Question and Answer |accessdate=2 March 2019 |date=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe controversy over the doctrine in the  [[Abassid]] caliphate came to a head during the reign of [[Caliph]] [[Al-Ma'mun|Abd Allah al-Ma\u2019mun]]. In 827 CE, al-Ma\u2019mun  publicly adopted the doctrine of createdness, and six year later instituting an inquisition known as the ''[[mihna]]'' (test or ordeal) to \u201censure acquiescence in this doctrine\u201d.<ref>John A. Nawas, \u201cA Reexamination of Three Current Explanations for al-Ma\u2019mun\u2019s Introduction of the Mihna.\u201d International Journal of Middle East Studies 26.4 (Nov. 1994): 615.</ref> According to Sunni tradition, when \"tested\", [[Muhaddith|traditionist]] [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]] refused to accept the doctrine of createdness despite two years imprisonment and being [[scourge]]d until unconscious. Eventually, due to Ahmad ibn Hanbal's determination,<ref name=WMP1897:2>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.2</ref> Caliph [[Al-Mutawakkil]] \u02bfAl\u0101 \u2019ll\u0101h, brought the ''[[mihna]]'' to an end and the [[Mu'tazila]] doctrine was silenced for a time.\n\nIn the years thereafter, it was the minority of Muslims who believed in Quranic createdness who were on the receiving end of the sword or lash.<ref name=SKHE-80>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=80|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Heaven+on+Earth:+A+Journey+Through+Shari%27a+Law#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20on%20Earth%3A%20A%20Journey%20Through%20Shari'a%20Law&f=false}}</ref>  \n\nThe influential scholar [[Al-Tabari]] (d.923)  declared in his ''[[aqidah]]'' (creed) that (in the words of Islamic historian [[Michael Cook (historian)|Michael Cook]]) the Quran is \n<blockquote>\"God's uncreated word however it is written or recited, whether it be in heaven or on earth, whether written on the `guarded tablet` or on the tablets of schoolboys, whether inscribed on stone or on paper, whether memorized in the heart or spoken on the tongue; whoever says otherwise is an infidel whose blood may be shed and from whom God has dissociated Himself.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Michael|title=The Koran : A Very Short Introduction|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/koranveryshorti00cook |url-access=registration|quote=The Koran : A Very Short Introduction.|page=[https://archive.org/details/koranveryshorti00cook/page/112 112] |isbn=0192853449 |ref=MCKVSI2000}}</ref></blockquote>  \n\n12th century [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] jurist [[Qadi Ayyad]], citing the work of [[Malik ibn Anas]], wrote that:\n\n<blockquote>He said about someone who said that the Qur'an is created, \"He is an unbeliever, so kill him.\" He said in the version of Ibn Nafi', \"He should be flogged and painfully beaten and imprisoned until he repents.\" In the version of Bishr ibn Bakr at-Tinnisi we find, \"He is killed and his repentance is not accepted.\" <ref>(Qadi 'Iyad Musa al-Yahsubi, Muhammad Messenger of Allah (Ash-Shifa of Qadi 'Iyad), translated by Aisha Abdarrahman Bewley [Madinah Press, Inverness, Scotland, U.K. 1991; third reprint, paperback], p. 419)</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Arguments and implications==\n===Shia===\n[[Ahlul Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project|Al-Islam.org]], a website which collects Shia scholarly works, cites Ash-Shaykh as-Saduq (aka Abu Ja'far Muhammad ibn 'Ali [[Ibn Babawayh]] al-Qummi  c.\u2009923\u2013991) as disagreeing with Sunnis on the issue of the Quran's createdness on the grounds that God's attributes of ''doing'' (creating, giving sustenance, etc.) cannot be eternal since they require objects to do actions ''to''. For this to be true, \"we will have to admit that the world has always existed. But it is against our belief that nothing except God is Eternal.\u201d<ref name=I\u2019tiqadat/> Author Allamah Sayyid Sa'eed Akhtar Rizvi goes on to say that Sunni scholars failure to make this distinction and insist that \"all His attributes are Eternal\" is the cause of their belief that \"the kalam (speech) of God, is Eternal, not created\".  Akhtar Rizvi states:\n<blockquote>But as we, the Shi'ah [[Twelver|Ithna \u2018ashari]]s, distinguish between His personal virtues and His actions, we say: [quoting Ibn Babawayh]\n\n\u201cOur belief about the Qur'an is that it is the speech of God. It has been sent by Him - it is His revelation, His book and His word. All is its Creator, Sender and Guardian...\u201d<ref name=I\u2019tiqadat>Al-I\u2019tiqadat. http://en.wikishia.net/view/Al-I%27tiqadat_(book) </ref><ref name=\"attributes\">{{cite web |last1=Sa'eed Akhtar Rizvi |first1=Allamah Sayyid |title=SECTS OF ISLAM. Attributes of Allah |url=https://www.al-islam.org/sects-islam-allamah-sayyid-saeed-akhtar-rizvi/attributes-allah |website=Al-Islam |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, the cite quotes another leading Shia Ayatullah Sayyid [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei|Abulqasim al-Khui]] (1899\u20131992) (in ''AL-BAYAN FI TAFSIR AL-QUR\u2019AN, THE PROLEGOMENA TO THE QUR\u2019AN''),  declaring that \"the question of whether the Qur'an was created or eternal is an extraneous matter that has no connection with the Islamic doctrine\", and blames the intrusion of the ideas of  alien \"Greek philosophy\" into the Muslim community for dividing the [[Ummah]] \"into factions which accused each other of disbelief\".<ref name=\"greek\">{{cite web |last1=Abulqasim al-Khui |title=AL-BAYAN FI TAFSIR AL-QUR\u2019AN, THE PROLEGOMENA TO THE QUR\u2019AN 13. The Qur'an: Created or Eternal with God? |url=https://www.al-islam.org/al-bayan-fi-tafsir-al-quran-prolegomena-quran-ayatullah-sayyid-abulqasim-al-khui/13-quran-created-or |website=Al-Islam |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mutazilah===\n\nThe adherents of the Mu\u02bftazili school, known as Mu\u02bftazilites, are best known for rejecting the doctrine of the Qur'an as uncreated and co-eternal with God,<ref name=as>Abdullah Saeed. ''The Qur'an: an introduction''. 2008, page 203</ref> asserting that if the Quran is the word of God, he [[logic]]ally \"must have preceded his own speech\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC}}</ref>\n\nBased on [[Al-Baqarah#Verse 2:106|Q.2:106]] some Mutazilah also argued that if the Qur'an could be subjected to abrogation, with a new verse abrogating an earlier one, it could not be eternal. Other Mutazilah however denied the theory of abrogation and did not believe any verse of the Quran was abrogated.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hasan |first1=Ahmad |title=The Theory of Naskh |journal=Islamic Studies |date=June 1965 |volume=4 |issue=2  |page=184 |ref=AHToN1965|jstor=20832797 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\nMalise Ruthven argues that believers in an uncreated Quran, and thus eternal and unchanging, also argued for [[predestination]] of the afterlife of mortals. The two ideas are associated with each other (according to Rwekaza Sympho Mukandala) because if there is predestination than God \"in His omnipotence and omniscience must have willed and known about\" events related in the Quran.<ref name=\"Mukandala-172\">{{cite book |last1=Mukandala |first1=Rwekaza Sympho |title=Justice, Rights and Worship: Religion and Politics in Tanzania |date=2006 |publisher=E & D Limited |page=172 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zvF4AAAAMAAJ&q=hadith+god%27s+speech+is+uncreated&dq=hadith+god%27s+speech+is+uncreated |accessdate=2 March 2019|isbn=9789987411313 }}</ref>\n\nBelievers in a created Quran emphasize free will given to mortals who would be rewarded or punished according to what they chose in life on judgement day. Advocates of the \"created\" Quran emphasized the references to an `Arabic` Quran which occur in the divine text; noting that if the Quran was uncreated it was \u2014 like God \u2014 an eternal being. This gave it (they argued) a status similar to God, constituting a form of bi-theism and thus [[Shirk (Islam)|shirk]].<ref name=\"Ruthven-192\">{{cite book |last1=Ruthven |first1=Malise |title=Islam in the World |date=1984 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-530503-6 |page=192 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=92lQfWj6_VIC&pg=PA192&dq=uncreated+quran#v=onepage&q=uncreated%20quran&f=false |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> \n\nRemi Brague argues that while a created Quran may be ''interpreted'' \"in the juridical sense of the word\",  an uncreated Quran can only be ''applied'' \u2014 the application being \"susceptible only \"to gramatical explication (tasfir) and mystical elucidation (ta'wil)\".<ref name=\"Brague\">{{cite book |last1=Brague |first1=R\u00e9mi |title=The Law of God: The Philosophical History of an Idea |date=2008 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |page=152 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=IE-vwiMn_sYC&pg=PA152&dq=uncreated+quran#v=onepage&q=uncreated%20quran&f=false |accessdate=28 February 2019|isbn=9780226070780 }}</ref>\n\n==Ahmad ibn Hanbal and the ''Mihna'' (ordeal)==\n{{main|Mihna}}\n===Ahmad ibn Hanbal===\nIn standing up for orthodoxy, Muslim scholar and muhaddith ibn Hanbal refused to engage in [[Muslim theology|kalam]] during his interrogation. He was willing to \u201cargue\u201d only on the basis of the Qur\u2019an or the traditions and their \u201cliteral\u201d meaning.<ref name=WMP1897:106>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.106</ref> While this distinction itself is difficult to make in practice, its value is in part rhetorical, for the assertion marks his orthodox identity as one who stands by the absolute authority of the sacred texts over-above those who make use of [[Mu'tazila#Reason and revelation|reason]].\nThe role of [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]] in the mihna ordeal garnered significant attention in the later [[Historiography of early Islam|historiography]] of Islam.  Walter Patton (in ''A\u1e25mad Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'') presents him as a stalwart of orthodoxy, claimed that he did more than any other to strengthen the position of [[orthodoxy]].<ref name=\"WMP1897:2\"/>\n\n===The ''Mihna''===\nScholars do not agree on why caliph al-Ma\u2019mun acted as he did.   Walter Patton for instance, claims that while partisans might have made political capital out of the public adoption of the doctrine, al-Ma\u2019mun\u2019s intention was \u201cprimarily to effect a religious reform.\u201d <ref name=WMP1897:54>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.54</ref> Nawas on the other hand, argues that the doctrine of createdness was a \u201cpseudo-issue,\u201d insisting that its promulgation was unlikely an end in itself since the primary sources attached so little significance to its declaration.<ref>Nawas, 1994: 623-624.</ref>\n\nThe test of the mihna was applied neither universally nor arbitrarily. In fact, the letter that Al-Ma\u2019mun sent to his lieutenant in Baghdad instituting the mihna stipulated that the test be administered to [[qadis]] and [[Muhaddith#Muhaddith|traditionists]] (muhaddithin). Both of these groups regard hadith as central to Qur\u2019anic interpretation and to matters of [[Fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]]. In particular, the rhetorical force of muhaddithin acceptance of the doctrine is then to concede that either or both of the Qur\u2019an and the hadith corpus attest to the doctrine, simultaneously validating the caliph\u2019s theological position and legitimizing his claim to hermeneutical authority with regard to the [[sacred texts]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{technical|date=October 2017}}\n{{too few opinions|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n\n== The significance of hadith ==\nThat the question of the createdness of the Qur\u2019an is, among other things, a [[hermeneutical]] issue is reflected in the variety of arguments and issues that associate with it \u2013 whether the Qur\u2019an or the traditions assert the Qur\u2019an\u2019s createdness, what \u201ccreated\u201d means, and whether and how this affects the standing of these texts as [[authoritative]] and as a consequence, the status of those who study them. Where the Qur\u2019an is understood as the word of God, and the words and example of [[Muhammad|the Prophet]] transmitted through [[hadith]] also attain to divine significance, if the Qur\u2019an cannot be taken to assert its own createdness, for the doctrine of createdness to be true the traditions would have to support it. Indeed, to admit the insufficiency of the hadith corpus to adjudicate what with the institution of the mihna becomes such a visible dispute would necessarily marginalize the authority of traditions. Thus it is not by accident that al-Ma\u2019mun decides to administer the test on [[Islamic scholar|religious scholars]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Biblical literalism]]\n* [[Exegesis]]\n* [[History of Islam]]\n* [[Ibn Kullab]]\n* [[Islam]]\n* [[Islamic schools and branches|Islamic Schools and Branches]]\n* [[Qur'anic exegesis|Qur\u2019anic exegesis]]\n* [[Sufficiency of Scripture#Sufficiency|Sufficiency of scripture]]\n\n== References ==\n{{cite book|first=Walter Melville |last=Patton|title=A\u1e25mad Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na: A Biography of the Im\u00e2m including an Account of the Mo\u1e25ammadan Inquisition Called the Mi\u1e25na: 218-234 A.H. |publisher=Leiden: E.J. Brill |date=1897 |url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100321026 |ref=WMP1897}}\n\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic theology]]\n[[Category:Hadith]]\n[[Category:Quran]]\n[[Category:9th century in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Mu'tazilism]]\n[[Category:827]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|doctrine that the Qur\u2019an was created, rather than having always existed; significant point of contention in early Islam}}\n\n{{Quran}}\n'''Createdness''' refers to the Islamic doctrinal position that the [[Qur\u2019an]] was created, rather than having always existed and thus being \"uncreated\". In the Muslim world the opposite point of view \u2014 that the Quran is uncreated \u2014 is the accepted stance among the majority [[Sunni]] Muslims while minority sects [[Shia]] [[Twelver]]s and [[Zaydi]], and the [[Kharijite]]s believe the Quran is created.<ref name=\"Glass\u00e9-268\">{{cite book|last1=Glass\u00e9|first1=Cyril|last2=Smith|first2=Huston|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|date=2002|publisher=Rowman Altamira.|page=268|edition=revised, reprinted|url=https://books.google.com/?id=focLrox-frUC&pg=PA268&dq=Uncreatedness+of+the+Quran#v=onepage&q=Uncreatedness%20of%20the%20Quran&f=false|accessdate=7 September 2015|isbn=9780759101906}}</ref> \n\nThe dispute over which was true became a significant point of contention in early Islam. The Islamic rationalist philosophical school known as the [[Mu'tazila]] held that if the Quran is God's word, logically God \"must have preceded his own speech\".<ref name=SKHE-77>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Heaven+on+Earth:+A+Journey+Through+Shari%27a+Law#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20on%20Earth%3A%20A%20Journey%20Through%20Shari'a%20Law&f=false}}</ref> The Qur'an, of course, expresses God's eternal will, but the work itself must have been created by Him at some point in time.<ref name=\"OISO\">{{cite web |title=Qur'an |url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/article/opr/t243/e275 |website=Oxford Islamic Studies Online |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nTraditionists, on the other hand, held that numerous  records of the words, actions, or approval of Muhammad (''[[a\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth]]'') support the contention that as God's speech, the Qur\u2019an is an attribute of God and therefore \"uncreated\".<ref name=\"islamQA-created\">{{cite web |last1=Saalih al-Munajjid |first1=Muhammad |title=The Qur'an is the word of Allah, may He be exalted, and is not created. 227441 |url=https://islamqa.info/en/answers/227441/the-quran-is-the-word-of-allah-may-he-be-exalted-and-is-not-created |website=Islam Question and Answer |accessdate=2 March 2019 |date=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe controversy over the doctrine in the  [[Abassid]] caliphate came to a head during the reign of [[Caliph]] [[Al-Ma'mun|Abd Allah al-Ma\u2019mun]]. In 827 CE, al-Ma\u2019mun  publicly adopted the doctrine of createdness, and six year later instituting an inquisition known as the ''[[mihna]]'' (test or ordeal) to \u201censure acquiescence in this doctrine\u201d.<ref>John A. Nawas, \u201cA Reexamination of Three Current Explanations for al-Ma\u2019mun\u2019s Introduction of the Mihna.\u201d International Journal of Middle East Studies 26.4 (Nov. 1994): 615.</ref> According to Sunni tradition, when \"tested\", [[Muhaddith|traditionist]] [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]] refused to accept the doctrine of createdness despite two years imprisonment and being [[scourge]]d until unconscious. Eventually, due to Ahmad ibn Hanbal's determination,<ref name=WMP1897:2>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.2</ref> Caliph [[Al-Mutawakkil]] \u02bfAl\u0101 \u2019ll\u0101h, brought the ''[[mihna]]'' to an end and the [[Mu'tazila]] doctrine was silenced for a time.\n\nIn the years thereafter, it was the minority of Muslims who believed in Quranic createdness who were on the receiving end of the sword or lash.<ref name=SKHE-80>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=80|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Heaven+on+Earth:+A+Journey+Through+Shari%27a+Law#v=onepage&q=Heaven%20on%20Earth%3A%20A%20Journey%20Through%20Shari'a%20Law&f=false}}</ref>  \n\nThe influential scholar [[Al-Tabari]] (d.923)  declared in his ''[[aqidah]]'' (creed) that (in the words of Islamic historian [[Michael Cook (historian)|Michael Cook]]) the Quran is \n<blockquote>\"God's uncreated word however it is written or recited, whether it be in heaven or on earth, whether written on the `guarded tablet` or on the tablets of schoolboys, whether inscribed on stone or on paper, whether memorized in the heart or spoken on the tongue; whoever says otherwise is an infidel whose blood may be shed and from whom God has dissociated Himself.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cook|first1=Michael|title=The Koran : A Very Short Introduction|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/koranveryshorti00cook |url-access=registration|quote=The Koran : A Very Short Introduction.|page=[https://archive.org/details/koranveryshorti00cook/page/112 112] |isbn=0192853449 |ref=MCKVSI2000}}</ref></blockquote>  \n\n12th century [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravid]] jurist [[Qadi Ayyad]], citing the work of [[Malik ibn Anas]], wrote that:\n\n<blockquote>He said about someone who said that the Qur'an is created, \"He is an unbeliever, so kill him.\" He said in the version of Ibn Nafi', \"He should be flogged and painfully beaten and imprisoned until he repents.\" In the version of Bishr ibn Bakr at-Tinnisi we find, \"He is killed and his repentance is not accepted.\" <ref>(Qadi 'Iyad Musa al-Yahsubi, Muhammad Messenger of Allah (Ash-Shifa of Qadi 'Iyad), translated by Aisha Abdarrahman Bewley [Madinah Press, Inverness, Scotland, U.K. 1991; third reprint, paperback], p. 419)</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Arguments and implications==\n===Shia===\n[[Ahlul Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project|Al-Islam.org]], a website which collects Shia scholarly works, cites Ash-Shaykh as-Saduq (aka Abu Ja'far Muhammad ibn 'Ali [[Ibn Babawayh]] al-Qummi  c.\u2009923\u2013991) as disagreeing with Sunnis on the issue of the Quran's createdness on the grounds that God's attributes of ''doing'' (creating, giving sustenance, etc.) cannot be eternal since they require objects to do actions ''to''. For this to be true, \"we will have to admit that the world has always existed. But it is against our belief that nothing except God is Eternal.\u201d<ref name=I\u2019tiqadat/> Author Allamah Sayyid Sa'eed Akhtar Rizvi goes on to say that Sunni scholars failure to make this distinction and insist that \"all His attributes are Eternal\" is the cause of their belief that \"the kalam (speech) of God, is Eternal, not created\".  Akhtar Rizvi states:\n<blockquote>But as we, the Shi'ah [[Twelver|Ithna \u2018ashari]]s, distinguish between His personal virtues and His actions, we say: [quoting Ibn Babawayh]\n\n\u201cOur belief about the Qur'an is that it is the speech of God. It has been sent by Him - it is His revelation, His book and His word. All is its Creator, Sender and Guardian...\u201d<ref name=I\u2019tiqadat>Al-I\u2019tiqadat. http://en.wikishia.net/view/Al-I%27tiqadat_(book) </ref><ref name=\"attributes\">{{cite web |last1=Sa'eed Akhtar Rizvi |first1=Allamah Sayyid |title=SECTS OF ISLAM. Attributes of Allah |url=https://www.al-islam.org/sects-islam-allamah-sayyid-saeed-akhtar-rizvi/attributes-allah |website=Al-Islam |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, the cite quotes another leading Shia Ayatullah Sayyid [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei|Abulqasim al-Khui]] (1899\u20131992) (in ''AL-BAYAN FI TAFSIR AL-QUR\u2019AN, THE PROLEGOMENA TO THE QUR\u2019AN''),  declaring that \"the question of whether the Qur'an was created or eternal is an extraneous matter that has no connection with the Islamic doctrine\", and blames the intrusion of the ideas of  alien \"Greek philosophy\" into the Muslim community for dividing the [[Ummah]] \"into factions which accused each other of disbelief\".<ref name=\"greek\">{{cite web |last1=Abulqasim al-Khui |title=AL-BAYAN FI TAFSIR AL-QUR\u2019AN, THE PROLEGOMENA TO THE QUR\u2019AN 13. The Qur'an: Created or Eternal with God? |url=https://www.al-islam.org/al-bayan-fi-tafsir-al-quran-prolegomena-quran-ayatullah-sayyid-abulqasim-al-khui/13-quran-created-or |website=Al-Islam |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mutazilah===\n\nThe adherents of the Mu\u02bftazili school, known as Mu\u02bftazilites, are best known for rejecting the doctrine of the Qur'an as uncreated and co-eternal with God,<ref name=as>Abdullah Saeed. ''The Qur'an: an introduction''. 2008, page 203</ref> asserting that if the Quran is the word of God, he [[logic]]ally \"must have preceded his own speech\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kadri|first1=Sadakat|title=Heaven on Earth: A Journey Through Shari'a Law from the Deserts of Ancient Arabia ...|date=2012|publisher=macmillan|isbn=9780099523277|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ztCRZOhJ10wC}}</ref>\n\nBased on [[Al-Baqarah#Verse 2:106|Q.2:106]] some Mutazilah also argued that if the Qur'an could be subjected to abrogation, with a new verse abrogating an earlier one, it could not be eternal. Other Mutazilah however denied the theory of abrogation and did not believe any verse of the Quran was abrogated.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hasan |first1=Ahmad |title=The Theory of Naskh |journal=Islamic Studies |date=June 1965 |volume=4 |issue=2  |page=184 |ref=AHToN1965|jstor=20832797 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\nMalise Ruthven argues that believers in an uncreated Quran, and thus eternal and unchanging, also argued for [[predestination]] of the afterlife of mortals. The two ideas are associated with each other (according to Rwekaza Sympho Mukandala) because if there is predestination than God \"in His omnipotence and omniscience must have willed and known about\" events related in the Quran.<ref name=\"Mukandala-172\">{{cite book |last1=Mukandala |first1=Rwekaza Sympho |title=Justice, Rights and Worship: Religion and Politics in Tanzania |date=2006 |publisher=E & D Limited |page=172 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zvF4AAAAMAAJ&q=hadith+god%27s+speech+is+uncreated&dq=hadith+god%27s+speech+is+uncreated |accessdate=2 March 2019|isbn=9789987411313 }}</ref>\n\nBelievers in a created Quran emphasize free will given to mortals who would be rewarded or punished according to what they chose in life on judgement day. Advocates of the \"created\" Quran emphasized the references to an `Arabic` Quran which occur in the divine text; noting that if the Quran was uncreated it was \u2014 like God \u2014 an eternal being. This gave it (they argued) a status similar to God, constituting a form of bi-theism and thus [[Shirk (Islam)|shirk]].<ref name=\"Ruthven-192\">{{cite book |last1=Ruthven |first1=Malise |title=Islam in the World |date=1984 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-530503-6 |page=192 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=92lQfWj6_VIC&pg=PA192&dq=uncreated+quran#v=onepage&q=uncreated%20quran&f=false |accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> \n\nRemi Brague argues that while a created Quran may be ''interpreted'' \"in the juridical sense of the word\",  an uncreated Quran can only be ''applied'' \u2014 the application being \"susceptible only \"to gramatical explication (tasfir) and mystical elucidation (ta'wil)\".<ref name=\"Brague\">{{cite book |last1=Brague |first1=R\u00e9mi |title=The Law of God: The Philosophical History of an Idea |date=2008 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |page=152 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=IE-vwiMn_sYC&pg=PA152&dq=uncreated+quran#v=onepage&q=uncreated%20quran&f=false |accessdate=28 February 2019|isbn=9780226070780 }}</ref>\n\n==Ahmad ibn Hanbal and the ''Mihna'' (ordeal)==\n{{main|Mihna}}\n===Ahmad ibn Hanbal===\nIn standing up for orthodoxy, Muslim scholar and muhaddith ibn Hanbal refused to engage in [[Muslim theology|kalam]] during his interrogation. He was willing to \u201cargue\u201d only on the basis of the Qur\u2019an or the traditions and their \u201cliteral\u201d meaning.<ref name=WMP1897:106>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.106</ref> While this distinction itself is difficult to make in practice, its value is in part rhetorical, for the assertion marks his orthodox identity as one who stands by the absolute authority of the sacred texts over-above those who make use of [[Mu'tazila#Reason and revelation|reason]].\nThe role of [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]] in the mihna ordeal garnered significant attention in the later [[Historiography of early Islam|historiography]] of Islam.  Walter Patton (in ''A\u1e25mad Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'') presents him as a stalwart of orthodoxy, claimed that he did more than any other to strengthen the position of [[orthodoxy]].<ref name=\"WMP1897:2\"/>\n\n===The ''Mihna''===\nScholars do not agree on why caliph al-Ma\u2019mun acted as he did.   Walter Patton for instance, claims that while partisans might have made political capital out of the public adoption of the doctrine, al-Ma\u2019mun\u2019s intention was \u201cprimarily to effect a religious reform.\u201d <ref name=WMP1897:54>[[#WMP1897|Patton, ''Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na'', 1897]]: p.54</ref> Nawas on the other hand, argues that the doctrine of createdness was a \u201cpseudo-issue,\u201d insisting that its promulgation was unlikely an end in itself since the primary sources attached so little significance to its declaration.<ref>Nawas, 1994: 623-624.</ref>\n\nThe test of the mihna was applied neither universally nor arbitrarily. In fact, the letter that Al-Ma\u2019mun sent to his lieutenant in Baghdad instituting the mihna stipulated that the test be administered to [[qadis]] and [[Muhaddith#Muhaddith|traditionists]] (muhaddithin). Both of these groups regard hadith as central to Qur\u2019anic interpretation and to matters of [[Fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]]. In particular, the rhetorical force of muhaddithin acceptance of the doctrine is then to concede that either or both of the Qur\u2019an and the hadith corpus attest to the doctrine, simultaneously validating the caliph\u2019s theological position and legitimizing his claim to hermeneutical authority with regard to the [[sacred texts]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{technical|date=October 2017}}\n{{too few opinions|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n\n== The significance of hadith ==\nThat the question of the createdness of the Qur\u2019an is, among other things, a [[hermeneutical]] issue is reflected in the variety of arguments and issues that associate with it \u2013 whether the Qur\u2019an or the traditions assert the Qur\u2019an\u2019s createdness, what \u201ccreated\u201d means, and whether and how this affects the standing of these texts as [[authoritative]] and as a consequence, the status of those who study them. Where the Qur\u2019an is understood as the word of God, and the words and example of [[Muhammad|the Prophet]] transmitted through [[hadith]] also attain to divine significance, if the Qur\u2019an cannot be taken to assert its own createdness, for the doctrine of createdness to be true the traditions would have to support it. Indeed, to admit the insufficiency of the hadith corpus to adjudicate what with the institution of the mihna becomes such a visible dispute would necessarily marginalize the authority of traditions. Thus it is not by accident that al-Ma\u2019mun decides to administer the test on [[Islamic scholar|religious scholars]].{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Biblical literalism]]\n* [[Exegesis]]\n* [[History of Islam]]\n* [[Ibn Kullab]]\n* [[Islam]]\n* [[Islamic schools and branches|Islamic Schools and Branches]]\n* [[Qur'anic exegesis|Qur\u2019anic exegesis]]\n* [[Sufficiency of Scripture#Sufficiency|Sufficiency of scripture]]\n\n== References ==\n{{cite book|first=Walter Melville |last=Patton|title=A\u1e25mad Ibn \u1e24anbal and the Mi\u1e25na: A Biography of the Im\u00e2m including an Account of the Mo\u1e25ammadan Inquisition Called the Mi\u1e25na: 218-234 A.H. |publisher=Leiden: E.J. Brill |date=1897 |url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100321026 |ref=WMP1897}}\n\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic theology]]\n[[Category:Hadith]]\n[[Category:Quran]]\n[[Category:9th century in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Mu'tazilism]]\n[[Category:827]]\n", "name_user": "Tridwoxi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"doctrine that the Qur\u2019an was created, rather than having always existed; significant point of contention in early Islam\" to \"Theological doctrine\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quranic_createdness"}
{"title_page": "2011\u201312 Montenegrin First League", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition      = [[Montenegrin First League]]\n| season           = 2011\u201312\n| winners          = [[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]] (2nd title)\n| relegated        = [[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]]<br>[[FK Berane|Berane]]<br>[[FK De\u010di\u0107|De\u010di\u0107]]\n| continentalcup1  = [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]\n| continentalcup2  = [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FK Rudar Pljevlja|Rudar]]<br>[[FK Zeta|Zeta]]<br>''[[FK \u010celik Nik\u0161i\u0107|\u010celik]] (via [[2011\u201312 Montenegrin Cup|cup]])''\n| matches          = 198\n| total goals      = 497\n| league topscorer = Admir Adrovi\u0107 (22)\n| biggest home win = [[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]] 6\u20130 [[FK Mladost Podgorica|Mladost]]\n| biggest away win = [[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]] 0\u20135 [[FK Mogren|Mogren]]\n| highest scoring  = [[FK Rudar Pljevlja|Rudar]] 6\u20132 [[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]]\n| prevseason       = [[2010\u201311 Montenegrin First League|2010\u201311]]\n| nextseason       = [[2012\u201313 Montenegrin First League|2012\u201313]]\n}}\n'''2011\u201312 [[Montenegrin First League]]''' is the sixth season of top-tier football in [[Montenegro]]. The season began on 6 August 2011 and will end at a yet unknown date in 2012, with a winter break beginning on 8 December 2011.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} [[FK Mogren|Mogren]] are the defending champions.\n\n== Teams ==\n[[OFK Bar|Bar]] were directly relegated to the Montenegrin Second League after finishing 12th at the end of [[2010\u201311 Montenegrin First League|last season]]; the club returned to the second level after just one year. Their place was taken by 2010\u201311 [[Montenegrin Second League|Second League]] champions [[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]], who returned to the top league of Montenegro after an absence of three seasons.\n\n10th-placed [[FK Mornar|Mornar]] and 11th-placed [[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]] had to compete in two-legged relegation play-offs. Sutjeska kept their place in the First League by beating Second League runners-up [[FK Jedinstvo Bijelo Polje|Jedinstvo Bijelo Polje]] 1\u20130 on aggregate. On the other hand, Mornar were relegated after losing to Second League third-placed team [[FK Berane]] on [[Away goals rule|away goals]]; the two-leg affair ended 1\u20131. Berane thus made their immediate return to the league, while Mornar were relegated after two seasons in the top flight.\n\n{{Location map+|Montenegro|float=right|width=250|caption=Location of teams in '''2010\u201311 Montenegrin First League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.84 |long=19.86 |label=[[FK Berane|Berane]] }}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.43 |long=18.77 |label=[[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]] |position=top }}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.365556 |long=19.331389 |label=[[FK De\u010di\u0107|De\u010di\u0107]] }}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.376712 |long=18.751988 |label=[[FK Grbalj|Grbalj]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.38 |long=18.92 |label=[[FK Lov\u0107en|Lov\u0107en]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.28 |long=18.83 |label=[[FK Mogren|Mogren]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.205556 |long=18.9425 |label=[[OFK Petrovac|Petrovac]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.444805 |long=19.264441 |label=<!--Podgorica--> }}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=43.36 |long=19.36 |label=[[FK Rudar Pljevlja|Rudar]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.78 |long=18.94 |label=[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]] }}\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|lat=42.335 |long=19.231111 |label=[[FK Zeta|Zeta]] |position=bottom}}\n<!--DISPLAY FIX FOR PODGORICA CLUBS-->\n{{Location map~|Montenegro|mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png |lat=42.5 |long=19.264441 |label=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]<br />[[FK Mladost Podgorica|Mladost]] }}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Team\n!City\n!Stadium\n!Capacity\n|-\n|[[FK Berane|Berane]]\n|[[Berane]]\n|[[Gradski Stadion Berane]]\n|align=\"center\" | 9,000\n|-\n|[[FK Bokelj|Bokelj]]\n|[[Kotor]]\n|[[Stadion pod Vrmcem]]\n|align=\"center\" | 3,000\n|-\n|[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]\n|[[Podgorica]]\n|[[Stadion Pod Goricom]]\n|align=\"center\" |12,000\n|-\n|[[FK De\u010di\u0107|De\u010di\u0107]]\n|[[Tuzi]]\n|[[Stadion Tu\u0161ko Polje]]\n|align=\"center\" |1,000\n|-\n|[[FK Grbalj|Grbalj]]\n|[[Radanovi\u0107i]]\n|[[Stadion u Radanovi\u0107ima]]\n|align=\"center\" |1,000\n|-\n|[[FK Lov\u0107en|Lov\u0107en]]\n|[[Cetinje]]\n|[[Stadion Obili\u0107a Poljana]]\n|align=\"center\" |1,000\n|-\n|[[FK Mladost Podgorica|Mladost]]\n|[[Podgorica]]\n|[[Stadion Cvijetni Brijeg]]\n|align=\"center\" |1,000\n|-\n|[[FK Mogren|Mogren]]\n|[[Budva]]\n|[[Stadion Lugovi]]\n|align=\"center\" |2,000\n|-\n|[[OFK Petrovac]]\n|[[Petrovac, Montenegro|Petrovac]]\n|[[Stadion Pod Malim Brdom]]\n|align=\"center\" |1,000\n|-\n|[[FK Rudar Pljevlja|Rudar]]\n|[[Pljevlja]]\n|[[Gradski stadion (Pljevlja)|Gradski stadion Pljevlja]]\n|align=\"center\" |7,000\n|-\n|[[FK Sutjeska Nik\u0161i\u0107|Sutjeska]]\n|[[Nik\u0161i\u0107]]\n|[[Stadion Gradski (Nik\u0161i\u0107)|Stadion kraj Bistrice]]\n|align=\"center\" |11,000\n|-\n|[[FK Zeta|Zeta]]\n|[[Golubovci]]\n|[[Tre\u0161njica Stadium|Stadion Tre\u0161njica]]\n|align=\"center\" |4,000\n|-\n|}\n{{-}}\n\n==League table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_limit=5\n|res_col_header=QR\n\n|team1=BUD|name_BUD=[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n|team2=RUD|name_RUD=[[FK Rudar Pljevlja|Rudar Pljevlja]]\n|team3=ZET|name_ZET=[[FK Zeta|Zeta]]\n|team4=MOG|name_MOG=[[FK Mogren|Mogren]]\n|team5=PET|name_PET=[[OFK Petrovac|Petrovac]]\n|team6=LOV|name_LOV=[[FK Lov\u0107en|Lov\u0107en]